<DOCNO> APW20000822.0005 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-22 00:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ex-Sailor Ordered To Stand Trial  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT (AP) -- A former Navy sailor charged with five murders
was ordered Monday to stand trial in the slaying of three
prostitutes.
</P>
<P>
   District Judge Maria Luisa Oxholm ruled during a preliminary
hearing that John Eric Armstrong, 26, should be tried in the
strangling deaths of three prostitutes from the Detroit area. He
already has been ordered to stand trial in two other killings.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Mitchell, Armstrong's attorney, previewed his likely
defense by contending that confessions authorities say Armstrong
made were coerced.
</P>
<P>
   ''These statements are suspect,'' Mitchell told the Detroit Free
Press for an article in Tuesday's editions. ''We're going to fight
them. ... I do not think they are voluntary.''
</P>
<P>
   In testimony Monday, police officer Donald Johnson read a
confession he attributed to Armstrong in which Armstrong, a husband
and father of two, described how he picked up one victim and paid
her $50 for sex.
</P>
<P>
   He told police he didn't remember strangling her, but he dumped
her out of his Jeep Wrangler when he realized she was not
breathing, Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't know why I did it. I'm sorry,'' Johnson read. ''I
didn't mean to. I don't know what happened. I'm truly sorry. I
didn't mean to kill her.''
</P>
<P>
   The five alleged murders and four attempted murders all involve
choking or strangulation and authorities say all victims are
prostitutes.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities also say Armstrong told them he killed at least a
dozen prostitutes worldwide when he was a sailor from 1993 to 1998.
FBI officials are still investigating the claims.
</P>
<P>
   If convicted of first-degree murder, he faces mandatory life in
prison.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-22-00 0018 </TRAILER>
