<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-22 00:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pedophile Murders Spark Outrage  </HEADLINE>
By ALESSANDRA RIZZO
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME (AP) -- The sex-slayings of two little girls over the
weekend in Italy prompted calls for chemical castration of sex
offenders and publishing the nams of pedophiles.
</P>
<P>
   ''Prison alone doesn't help,'' Alessandra Mussolini, a
legislator from the right-wing National Alliance, told the ANSA
news agency.
</P>
<P>
   Mussolini, the granddaughter of Fascist dictator Benito
Mussolini, on Monday suggested chemical castration or lifetime
confinement in medical institutions as alternatives to prison.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmaker Maretta Scoca of the centrist UDEUR party also called
for chemical castration, in which drugs are used to reduce the
amount of the male hormone testosterone the body produces.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Gianni Baget Bozo, a priest tied to the conservative
Forza Italia political alliance, told ANSA that the suggestion of
chemical castration was a ''Nazi'' idea. Studies also have
questioned its effectiveness.
</P>
<P>
   The two murders shocked the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of people in the southern Puglia region attended the
funeral Monday of 8-year-old Graziella Mansi, who was sexually
assaulted and then burned alive. An 18-year-old, Pasquale Tortora,
has confessed.
</P>
<P>
   Mansi was slain Saturday, one day after the murder of a
5-year-old Tunisian immigrant in Imperia on the Italian Riviera.
Hagere Kilani was abducted, raped and repeatedly stabbed by a
Romanian immigrant who fled to France, police said.
</P>
<P>
   A group fighting child abuse offered to make a list available of
140 convicted pedophiles in the Tuscany and Umbria regions. The
list was compiled from court decisions.
</P>
<P>
   Italy's social affairs minister, Livia Turco, rejected the idea
as ''useless and harmful'' and said ''the experience in England
should tell us a lot of things.''
</P>
<P>
   Two men in Britain committed suicide earlier this month after a
tabloid newspaper published names, photos and locations of alleged
pedophiles.
</P>
<P>
   ''When fundamental rights are at stake ... we must stick to law
and legality,'' Turco told the Milan daily Corriere della Sera.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-22-00 0037 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
