<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-22 02:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thousands of phone workers back on job, others still striking  </HEADLINE>
By KALPANA SRINIVASAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) - Verizon Communications and negotiators
representing 35,000 employees in six states and the District of
Columbia reported some progress toward reaching a contract to end a
strike that is more than two weeks old.
</P>
<P>
   About 50,000 workers in New York and New England, whose union
representatives reached tentative agreements with the company over
the weekend, left the picket lines Monday and returned to the job.
</P>
<P>
   They started working on a backlog of 280,000 repair requests and
new installation orders that have piled up since the strike began
Aug. 6. Company officials estimated it will take three to four
weeks to clear the backlog.
</P>
<P>
   The company is still negotiating with the bargaining unit that
represents workers in the mid-Atlantic states. Candice Johnson,
spokeswoman for the Communications Workers of America, said late
Monday that there was some progress.
</P>
<P>
   ''We still need to resolve some pretty key issues for our
members,'' she said. Members of the union remained on the picket
lines Monday in Pennsylvania, New Jersey, Delaware, Maryland,
Virginia, West Virginia and the District of Columbia.
</P>
<P>
   Forced overtime levels for customer service representatives and
monitoring of those workers are unresolved issues, union officials
said.
</P>
<P>
   Deana Rouse, one of a dozen Verizon service representatives
carrying a red picket sign outside company headquarters in Newark,
N.J., Monday said employees are forced to work two hours overtime
five days a week and often work on weekends.
</P>
<P>
   ''You don't have much time to spend with your family,'' Rouse
said.
</P>
<P>
   Verizon executives said the negotiations with that unit are
centered on resolving local matters, but said they believe the
talks could have been wrapped by now.
</P>
<P>
   ''These are relatively simple issues that could have been and
should have been settled'' Sunday night, said Lawrence T. Babbio
Jr., company vice chairman and president.
</P>
<P>
   Verizon, a company formed by the summer merger of Bell Atlantic
and GTE, reached agreements with the International Brotherhood of
Electrical Workers and another CWA bargaining unit Sunday. Union
members must still ratify the three-year contracts.
</P>
<P>
   As a result of the talks, the unions also won an agreement to
let them try organizing workers in the company's largely
non-unionized wireless division using signup cards rather than
holding a representation election.
</P>
<P>
   The unions must get signed cards from 55 percent of wireless
workers in a specific group to represent them. Labor leaders say
the process is less cumbersome and faster than holding
secret-ballot elections.
</P>
<P>
   Both organizers and company management stipulated to neutrality
clauses allowing both sides to present their position on
unionization to employees. Only 46 workers, in a work force of
32,000 wireless employees, are union members now.
</P>
<P>
   The card-signing campaign would begin in six months. The union
can begin a similar campaign to organize employees in Verizon's
wireless retail stores in a year, under the tentative accord.
</P>
<P>
   Highlights of the tentative agreements include:
</P>
<P>
   -A 12 percent increase in wages over the life of the three-year
contracts. Customer service representatives will receive an
additional 4 percent wage increase effective immediately.
</P>
<P>
   -An effort by the company to reduce required overtime over the
next year to about 8 hours per week for technicians. Verizon
preserves a right to require more time in emergencies or other
situations.
</P>
<P>
   -Bonuses of up to 10 percent for workers meeting higher service
and performance standards.
</P>
<P>
   -All union-covered employees will get by year's end options for
purchasing 100 shares of Verizon stock.
</P>
<P>
   -Greater access for unions workers to jobs in the company's
high-speed Internet business.
</P>
<P>
   -A limit of 0.7 percent on the number of jobs in any region that
can be moved to another area in a year. Unions had feared that
Verizon would shift work to areas of cheaper labor within its newly
expanded territory.
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: Verizon Communications: http://www.verizon.com
</P>
<P>
   Communications Workers of America: http://www.cwa-union.org
</P>
<P>
   International Brotherhood of Electrical Workers:
http://www.ibew.org
</P>
</TEXT>
