<HEADLINE> Car Dealer To Offer Gun Giveaway  </HEADLINE>
By DUNCAN MANSFIELD
<TEXT>
<P>
   KNOXVILLE, Tenn. (AP) -- With deer-hunting season fast
approaching, car dealer Greg ''Lumpy'' Lambert took a shot in the
dark with a new promotion: a gun voucher with every auto sale and a
water pistol for every child.
</P>
<P>
   Gun opponents aren't happy about his planned ''Second
Amendment'' sales campaign set for Saturday, but Lambert said that
most of the calls he has gotten have been fairly positive or
neutral.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are in East Tennessee,'' he said Monday. ''This is a
sportsman's paradise. We thought just before fall, just before
deer-hunting season, that it might be nice to have a promotion like
this.''
</P>
<P>
   Lambert, 34, runs a small family-owned car lot called Advantage
Auto Sales in a Knoxville suburb. He typically has 15 to 20 used
cars for sale at any one time.
</P>
<P>
   He plans to offer vouchers for a bolt-action, 8 mm deer rifle,
valued at around $100. The vouchers will be voided if the holders
aren't qualified to own a gun.
</P>
<P>
   ''From a business standpoint, if I sell a couple of cars or if I
just get people to come out and look at what I have, I will
consider it a success,'' Lambert said of the promotion.
</P>
<P>
   ''If it in any way helps promote responsible and safe firearms
ownership, then from a political standpoint, it will be an
overwhelming success,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   A Knoxville minister criticized Lambert's plan to give away toy
guns.
</P>
<P>
   ''Rifles have legitimate purposes,'' said the Rev. Tom Rhodes of
Westside Unitarian Universalist Church. ''It is deeply disturbing
that they will be giving toy firearms to children. I don't think
even the NRA would support that.''
</P>
<P>
   Naomi Paiss, a spokeswoman for Washington-based Handgun Control
Inc., called the entire promotion irresponsible.
</P>
<P>
   ''If it is possible to further lower the image of used car
salesmen,'' she told The Knoxville News-Sentinel, ''this guy has
done it.''
</P>
<P>
   Similar gun giveaways and raffles across the country in the past
year have met with mixed success. In January, the Los Angeles
County Sheriff's Department abandoned a raffle after gun control
advocates complained.
</P>
<P>
   But the previous month, a Future Farmers of America chapter at a
North Carolina school, expecting to raise several thousand dollars
for a building project, instead earned more than $20,000 by
raffling five guns.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net
</P>
<P>
   The NRA site: http://www.nra.org
</P>
<P>
   Handgun Control: http://www.handguncontrol.org
</P>
</TEXT>
