<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Primaries in Alaska, Okla., Wyoming  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated Press	   Oklahoma Democrats hope to position themselves to
recapture an
open House seat in a district where they outnumber Republicans as
three states hold primaries on Tuesday.
<TEXT>
<P>
   No primary opponents rose to challenge two top Republicans in
Wyoming and Alaska, while a GOP House member in Wyoming is up
against two poorly funded challengers.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Craig Thomas of Wyoming, a first-term Republican, faced no
primary opposition. GOP Rep. Don Young, Alaska's lone House member,
also saw no challengers for his party's nomination.
</P>
<P>
   In Oklahoma, three Democrats and seven Republicans are seeking
their parties' nominations for a seat left open by GOP Rep. Tom
Coburn, who kept a campaign promise to retire after three terms.
Democrats, who outnumber Republicans 5-to-2 in the district, held
the seat until Coburn's victory in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats seeking the nomination include state Rep. Bill Settle
and James ''Jim Bob'' Wilson, who campaigns on the fact he is not a
lawyer. Coburn's chosen successor is Republican car dealer Andy
Ewing. Another GOP candidate is Mark Detro, who faces drug and
assault-and-battery charges.
</P>
<P>
   In Wyoming, Thomas reported more than $500,000 in campaign
donations. The two Democrats seeking the nomination to challenge
him in the fall had not raised the $5,000 required to trigger
federal disclosures.
</P>
<P>
   Three-term Wyoming Rep. Barbara Cubin faces two fellow
Republican challengers who raised so little money that they didn't
meet requirements to file fund-raising disclosures in July. She had
more than $130,000 on hand earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
   GOP Rep. Don Young, Alaska's lone House member, also has no
challengers for his party's nomination. Three poorly funded
Democrats are seeking their party's nomination to challenge Young,
who has represented the state since 1973.
</P>
<P>
   Oklahoma voters will also decide whether to lower the cost of
car tags, cutting taxes overall by an estimated $22.3 million.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-22-00 0244 </TRAILER>
