<DOCNO> APW20000822.0036 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-22 02:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hastert: Clinton Wrong on Tax Cuts  </HEADLINE>
By CURT ANDERSON
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Republican tax cuts passed by Congress this
year would consume far less of the budget surplus than the White
House claims, House Speaker Dennis Hastert said in a letter to
President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Hastert, R-Ill., included a plea for cooperation on year-end
budget negotiations in the letter Monday even as he called the
president ''wildly'' wrong in contending the tax cuts would cost
nearly $2 trillion over 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   ''Mr. President, let's get the people's work done and not play
politics with the budget process,'' Hastert said. ''We proved last
year we could reach agreement, and we can do it again.''
</P>
<P>
   Hastert said White House spending proposals of $1 trillion over
10 years would dwarf the GOP tax cuts of about half that size and
pose a greater threat to reaching a budget compromise before
Congress adjourns for the fall election campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has frequently contended that tax cuts passed or moving
in this year's GOP-led Congress, coupled with tax cuts passed last
year, would total $1.8 trillion over the next decade including
higher interest payments on public debt and would consume nearly
all of the projected budget surplus.
</P>
<P>
   Many of this year's cuts, however, duplicate those passed last
year, such as gradual repeal of the estate tax. Citing new
nonpartisan Joint Committee on Taxation estimates, Hastert said
this year's Congress has actually passed $531.5 billion in tax cuts
over 10 years -- or about 11.6 percent of the total projected
surplus of $4.56 trillion.
</P>
<P>
   ''Your assertion that Republicans have passed nearly $2 trillion
in tax relief is wildly off the mark,'' Hastert told the president.
''We can afford to provide some common-sense tax relief to the
American people, whose hard work and tax dollars build up this
surplus.''
</P>
<P>
   In response, White House Chief of Staff John Podesta told
Hastert in a letter that the administration wants to ''work
together on fiscally responsible'' tax cuts and spending
priorities.
</P>
<P>
   ''As it now stands, however, your party continues to support an
irresponsible tax strategy that abandons the fiscal discipline that
led our country out of deficits and toward the economic prosperity
we enjoy today,'' Podesta said.
</P>
<P>
   Podesta added that over 10 years, Republican tax cuts Congress
passed this year would take $900 billion of the surplus, counting
interest. The White House adds to that figure tax cuts of $1.3
trillion proposed by GOP presidential nominee George W. Bush. When
duplicate items are eliminated, Podesta said, the total cuts amount
to about $2 trillion.
</P>
<P>
   Hastert will join Clinton on a one-day trip Aug. 30 to Colombia,
giving the two time to discuss the issues.
</P>
<P>
   The $531.5 billion figure cited by Hastert has one flaw: It
assumes budget rules mandating that the marriage penalty tax cut
vetoed by Clinton expire after five years, costing $89.8 billion.
If continued through the entire decade, that bill would have
ballooned to $292 billion, bringing the total in GOP tax cuts this
year to more than $733 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Hastert also told Clinton it was ''disappointing'' that Senate
Democrats have blocked legislation that would formally lock away
all Social Security and Medicare surpluses only for those programs.
Republicans and Democrats have, however, agreed to honor these
''lockboxes'' and pay down more than $220 billion in public debt.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers have much work to do when they return from recess in
early September. Only two of the 13 annual government spending
bills for the fiscal year beginning Oct. 1 have been signed into
law and there are major disagreements on many others. No one,
however, envisions a government shutdown confrontation like that of
1995.
</P>
<P>
   GOP aides say Republicans are likely to try for one final tax
bill, most likely including an expansion of contributions to
individual retirement accounts and 401(k)s, new taxpayer rights and
a measure backed by Clinton to boost private investment and make
capital available in poor inner cities and rural areas.
</P>
<P>
   --------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Congress: http://thomas.loc.gov
</P>
</TEXT>
