<HEADLINE> Time capsule of 1873 goes online  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   ROCHESTER, N.Y. (AP) - People who want to see the contents of an
1873 city of Rochester time capsule need only to click onto the
World Wide Web.
</P>
<P>
   By clicking onto the Web site - www.rochestertimecapsule.com -
those interested can read, hear and see the contents of the copper
box taken from the old City Hall in May.
</P>
<P>
   And the Web site, which debuted Monday, welcomes suggestions for
the contents of a new Rochester time capsule to be buried next
year. It also invites messages and predictions for future
generations.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't know of another place where you would go to get such a
complete account of a time capsule,'' said Connie Bodner, director
of collections and research at the Rochester Museum &AMP; Science
Center.
</P>
<P>
   The time capsule's contents are on display at the museum, but
Bodner stresses that the Web site will reach people who can't come
to the museum, just as it will help teachers and students.
</P>
<P>
   The Web site lists, pictures and describes most of the capsule's
items. It also includes transcriptions of letters, such as that of
Rochester merchant William Scrantom to the mayor of Rochester at
the time of the capsule's opening.
</P>
</TEXT>
