<DOCNO> APW20000822.0042 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-22 02:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gore To Stress Vietnam Service  </HEADLINE>
By BRIGITTE GREENBERG
<TEXT>
<P>
   MILWAUKEE (AP) -- A day after George W. Bush told veterans the
Clinton-Gore administration had all but ruined the military, Al
Gore was delivering the opposite message, telling the same group
that America's fighting forces are the strongest and most modern in
the world.
</P>
<P>
   Gore was to stress his experience as a Vietnam veteran in
remarks Tuesday to the annual convention of the Veterans of Foreign
Wars, his spokesman Chris Lehane said. Gore was an Army journalist
in Vietnam; Bush was a fighter jet pilot in the Texas Air National
Guard.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, the Democratic presidential candidate, also planned to
highlight his role in military affairs while serving in the House
and Senate, Lehane said. One example likely to be mentioned is that
Gore and running mate Joseph Lieberman both crossed party lines in
the Senate to vote in favor of the Persian Gulf War, a conflict
opposed by most Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   ''Based both on his public and his private experiences, he feels
that the approach we have taken over the last eight years and the
approach he's taken through the agenda he has put forth is the
right approach,'' Lehane said.
</P>
<P>
   That $127 billion agenda includes higher pay for personnel,
investments to modernize equipment and more funding for veterans
hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   Republican presidential rival Bush has proposed pumping billions
into service member pay and spending $310 million program to fix
schools on military bases.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Bush told the VFW that U.S. forces are overextended
in deployments overseas. Under the Clinton-Gore administration,
there has been an average of one new deployment every nine weeks,
while defense spending has declined nearly 40 percent, Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   ''The next president will inherit a military in decline,'' he
said. ''As president, I will rebuild the military power of the
United States.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore's campaign said the administration has reversed a decline
in defense spending that it said began when Republicans ruled the
White House.
</P>
<P>
   Defense Secretary William Cohen, a Republican, also took issue
with Bush's assertion, pointing to an administration proposal to
boost Pentagon spending by $112 billion through 2005.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think you will see a military on the ascendancy,'' said
Cohen, who addressed the VFW gathering earlier Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Lehane said Gore would report to the 1.9 million member VFW that
''we have the best prepared, most powerful, most modern military in
history.''
</P>
<P>
   Cuts in defense spending date back to 1986 and the Reagan
administration, and military expenditures as a percentage of the
gross national product declined each year after that through the
administration of Bush's father.
</P>
<P>
   The fiscal 1989 defense budget was $295 billion, dropping to
$262 billion in 1991. The fiscal 2001 defense spending bill Clinton
signed two weeks ago totaled $288 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the administration signed a 4.8 percent military pay
increase, the largest in a generation, and Gore supports an
additional 3.7 percent pay increase enacted this month.
</P>
<P>
   Bush advocates additional pay hikes of $1 billion a year over
five years. Gore says the size of Bush's proposed $1 trillion,
10-year tax cut would leave little funds for such a big pay hike.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking at a rally in Quincy, Ill., near the end of their
post-convention tour, Lieberman said Gore, as vice president, has
been ''fighting to keep America's military and make it, frankly,
the best-equipped, best-trained, most powerful fighting force in
the history of the world.''
</P>
<P>
   ''And we'll keep it that way when Al is elected president,''
Lieberman added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-22-00 0249 </TRAILER>
