<DOCNO> APW20000822.0043 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-22 02:54 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Helton Reaches .400, Then Falls  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER (AP) -- Todd Helton reached the .400 mark with two
singles, then fell back a point when he struck out in the eighth
inning Monday night for the Colorado Rockies against Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   After his soft single to center off Kevin Millwood in the sixth
inning, Helton's average was an even .400. He is the first person
since George Brett to reach that mark this late in the season.
</P>
<P>
   Helton struck out against reliever Mike Remlinger, dropping him
to .399.
</P>
<P>
   Brett was hitting above .400 on Sept. 4, 1980. Helton already
has surpassed the 502 plate appearances needed to qualify for the
batting title.
</P>
<P>
   Helton has captured the nation's attention on the strength of an
impressive August. With two hits in four at-bats Monday night, he
was 27-for-46 (.587) during a 13-game hitting streak.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
