<DOCNO> APW20000822.0049 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-22 08:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hurricane Debby Threatens Caribbean  </HEADLINE>
By MARVIN HOKSTAM
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILIPSBURG, St. Maarten (AP) -- Islanders and tourists scrambled
to prepare for Hurricane Debby as the storm gained strength and
threatened to make landfall Tuesday in the Caribbean.
</P>
<P>
   The storm, with maximum sustained winds of 75 mph, was moving
west-northwest along the northern Leeward Islands early Tuesday, at
speeds near 21 mph. Shortly after 5 a.m., the eye was located 40
miles southeast of St. Maarten, the National Weather Service said.
</P>
<P>
   Schools closed on Monday, people stocked emergency supplies,
governments prepared shelters and tourists crowded airports to
flee, even as airlines canceled flights. Cruise ships turned away
from the wind and rain.
</P>
<P>
   Dangerous battering waves and 4 to 6 inches of rain were
expected in the path of the storm, which emerged with unnerving
suddenness over the weekend and became the first hurricane of the
storm season to threaten landfall.
</P>
<P>
   In the U.S. territory of Puerto Rico, there were fears of a
direct hit on the capital, San Juan, which could bring
life-threatening flash floods and mudslides.
</P>
<P>
   ''Right now it looks like its coming directly here,'' forecaster
Ed Tirado said from the San Juan office of the National Weather
Service.
</P>
<P>
   A tropical storm becomes a hurricane when sustained winds reach
74 miles per hour. Debby was upgraded to a hurricane overnight, and
forecasters expected the storm to strengthen further.
</P>
<P>
   Hurricane warnings were in effect from Guadeloupe northwest
through the British and the U.S. Virgin islands and Puerto Rico. A
hurricane warning was issued for the north coast of the vulnerable,
populous Dominican Republic.
</P>
<P>
   A hurricane watch was issued in the southeastern Bahamas, and
one remained in effect for northern Haiti.
</P>
<P>
   Lightning flashed across San Juan Bay early Tuesday and gusting
winds carrying a torrent of rain bent palm trees along the
waterfront.
</P>
<P>
   Hurricane force winds extended outward up to 25 miles, and
tropical storm force winds extended outward up to 175 miles, mainly
to the north of the center, the weather service said.
</P>
<P>
   Ten ships and two submarines in the USS Harry Truman battle
group abandoned training exercises off the Puerto Rican island of
Vieques -- the site of recurrent protest over military exercises --
and moved 300 miles south, the Navy said.
</P>
<P>
   Forecasters said it was too early to gauge the threat to the
U.S. mainland.
</P>
<P>
   In the U.S. Virgin Islands, the National Park Service closed its
grounds on St. John. Boaters moored off the island park were told
to move to safe harbors. Hotels refused new reservations as their
guests tried to flee the storm.
</P>
<P>
   ''Lots of people want to leave today but unfortunately most of
the flights are already sold out,'' said travel agent Angela
Belfon.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Shepherd of Richmond, Virginia, vacationing with his family,
decided to leave early.
</P>
<P>
   ''You never know with a hurricane,'' he said at St. Thomas
airport.
</P>
<P>
   In volcano-plagued Montserrat, southwest of Antigua, British
Gov. Anthony Abbott warned citizens in a radio address to prepare
for Debby. Stormy weather could cause mudslides of volcanic debris
down the Belham River, the Montserrat Volcano Observatory warned.
</P>
<P>
   In Antigua, electricity went out and motorists lined up for gas.
People living in roofless homes since last year's hurricane headed
for shelters.
</P>
<P>
   To the west, in the twin-island nation of St. Kitts and Nevis,
Debby threatened to soak Carifesta, a 35-nation arts and music
festival that began Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere, Hurricane Alberto, the longest-lived August tropical
storm on record, was moving in a circle in the north Atlantic.
Alberto formed Aug. 4 and hasn't threatened land.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   National Hurricane Center: http://www.nhc.noaa.gov
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-22-00 0851 </TRAILER>
