<HEADLINE> Stocks Open Higher Early On  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks bobbed higher this morning in anxious
trading before a Federal Reserve meeting in which the central bank
was expected to leave interest rates unchanged.
</P>
<P>
   In the first half hour of trading on Wall Street, the Dow Jones
industrial average was up 27.11 at 11,106.92.
</P>
<P>
   Broader stock indicators were also posting slim gains. The
Nasdaq composite index was up 19.04 at 3,972.19, the Standard &AMP;
Poor's 500 index was up 0.69 at 1,500.17, and the Russell 2000
index of smaller companies was up 0.79 at 517.24.
</P>
<P>
   Trading has been light in recent sessions as traders awaited
Tuesday's meeting at the Federal Reserve. Thanks to a stream of
data suggesting the Fed has succeeded in containing inflation with
a year-long program of interest rate hikes, analysts believe the
central bank won't move to slow the economy again on Tuesday or any
time soon.
</P>
<P>
   Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a slender margin on
the New York Stock Exchange, while Nasdaq gainers held a larger
lead.
</P>
<P>
   Overseas, Japan's Nikkei stock average rose 2.58 percent. In
afternoon trading, Germany's DAX index was up 0.57 percent,
Britain's FT-SE 100 was up 0.59 percent, and France's CAC-40 was up
0.31 percent.
</P>
