<HEADLINE> Kentucky Senator Home After Surgery  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Sen. Jim Bunning is back home in Kentucky
after undergoing surgery to remove his gallbladder and a benign
tumor.
</P>
<P>
   Bunning was released Monday from the Mayo Clinic in Rochester,
Minn., where surgery was performed Aug. 15, his office said in a
statement.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican senator ''is continuing to recuperate at his home
in Southgate. He is extremely grateful to everyone who has sent
their well wishes,'' the statement said.
</P>
<P>
   After attending the Republican National Convention in
Philadelphia, Bunning, 68, underwent a medical evaluation that
found he had an inflamed gallbladder and a benign mass on his left
adrenal gland.
</P>
<P>
   Bunning spokesman John Mechem said the senator expects to resume
his duties in Washington when Congress returns on Sept. 6.
</P>
<P>
   Bunning had a 12-year House career before entering the Senate in
1998, but he is probably best known for his 17-year baseball
career. As a pitcher for the Detroit Tigers and the Philadelphia
Phillies, Bunning recorded two no-hitters and 200-plus victories
and earned him a spot in the Hall of Fame.
</P>
</TEXT>
