<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Burundi Leader Cancels Trip  </HEADLINE>
By JOCELYNE SAMBIRA
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUJUMBURA, Burundi (AP) -- President Pierre Buyoya canceled a
trip to South Africa and a meeting with mediator Nelson Mandela on
Tuesday, and instead focused on calming Tutsi opposition to a peace
agreement aimed at ending the country's civil war.
</P>
<P>
   Tensions in the tiny central African country have increased
dramatically in recent weeks as a deadline neared for signing the
power-sharing agreement, set by Mandela for Aug. 28.
</P>
<P>
   The former South African president has been mediating peace
talks since December and has invited President Clinton and other
world leaders to witness the signing of the accord in the northern
Tanzanian town of Arusha.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement requires the minority Tutsis to relinquish power
in the government and army, and set up ethnically balanced
institutions in an effort to end the civil war that broke out in
October 1993. The war has left more than 200,000 people -- most of
them civilians -- dead.
</P>
<P>
   Army officials said Tuesday that one soldier was wounded when
Hutu rebels opened fire on an army truck on a road east of
Bujumbura.
</P>
<P>
   Col. Samuel Gahiro, commander of the First Military District in
Bujumbura, said the attack was repulsed, but did not give rebel
casualties.
</P>
<P>
   Buyoya warned Tutsi hard-liners Monday, who have demonstrated
against the peace accord with Hutus, not to attempt a coup against
him.
</P>
<P>
   Appolinaire Gahungu, the presidential spokesman, said Buyoya
would not travel outside Burundi until at least the weekend. He
said Buyoya would chair a cabinet meeting Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Buyoya, a retired Tutsi major who seized power in a 1996 coup,
is under increasing pressure from middle-class Tutsis and the
Tutsi-dominated army, his main constituencies, not to sign the
accord which they say favors the majority Hutus.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Nzeyimana, leader of a Tutsi political party, said his
and nine other Tutsi political parties had written to Mandela,
Clinton and other leaders in an attempt to renegotiate virtually
all issues in the accord.
</P>
<P>
   ''We will not sign the agreement in its present form,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The civil war started when Tutsi paratroopers assassinated
Melchior Ndadaye, the first democratically elected president and a
Hutu.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
