<BODY>
<HEADLINE> N. Korea, Japan Argue Over Past  </HEADLINE>
By JOJI SAKURAI
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- Japan and North Korea quarreled over long-standing
grievances Tuesday in talks on normalizing relations, a sign that
the Stalinist North's recent diplomatic offensive has not soothed
all tensions with its former colonial ruler.
</P>
<P>
   In what had been expected to be a courtesy call on Foreign
Minister Yohei Kono, top North Korean envoy Jong Thae Hwa blamed
the lack of official ties on Japan's refusal to make amends for its
1910-1945 rule over Korea, said a Japanese foreign ministry
official who was at the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Kono demanded information on Japanese citizens allegedly
abducted by North Korea to serve as language teachers for spies,
the official said in a briefing given on condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   Kono championed the cause of relatives of the missing, who
gathered outside the conference hall at the Foreign Ministry and
shouted ''Give them back!'' as limousines carrying the North Korean
delegation passed the gate.
</P>
<P>
   ''When one thinks of these people ... they have had such a
difficult experience. I would like North Korea to aggressively
investigate,'' Kono told Jong, according to the official.
</P>
<P>
   The talks in Tokyo, scheduled to last until Thursday, are the
second round of negotiations begun in Pyongyang four months ago.
The first meeting restarted discussions after an eight-year
suspension.
</P>
<P>
   After the Kono-Jong meeting, the two countries' negotiating
teams met for about an hour, each presenting its positions.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides said they were more hopeful because of the recent
thaw between North and South Korea, whose leaders met in June and
agreed to work toward reunification, the official said.
</P>
<P>
   Japan's chief negotiator, Kojiro Takano, said a similar detente
between Tokyo and Pyongyang would make North Asia a safer region.
</P>
<P>
   ''In order to contribute to Northeast Asian stability and peace,
I want to work hard toward correcting the irregular relations that
have existed... since the end of World War II,'' Takano told Jong,
according to the official.
</P>
<P>
   But Tuesday's talks also evoked the sparring by Japanese and
North Korean negotiators at the April talks in Pyongyang.
</P>
<P>
   The Foreign Ministry official said in the briefing that his
impression was that the two sides have not budged on the main
issues.
</P>
<P>
   Takano suggested that the kidnappings would have to be addressed
in any agreement in order to win the backing of the Japanese public
and Parliament, the official said.
</P>
<P>
   North Korea agreed during talks with the Red Cross in December
to investigate allegations by the Japanese government that its
agents abducted at least 10 Japanese citizens.
</P>
<P>
   Jong told Takano that the North remains immovable on its
principal demands -- compensation and apology for colonization, a
return of cultural treasures allegedly carted off by Japanese
soldiers, and improvements in the legal status of Koreans living in
Japan.
</P>
<P>
   But he hinted that he still hoped for an agreement by the agreed
target of the end of this year.
</P>
<P>
   ''If we leave problems of the 20th century to be solved in the
21st, we will have failed in our historical responsibility,'' Jong
told Takano, according to the official.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
