<HEADLINE> Ex-Azerbaijan President Dies  </HEADLINE>
By LOUIS MEIXLER
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANKARA, Turkey (AP) -- Abulfaz Elchibey, a former dissident who
became the first elected president of Azerbaijan following the 1991
breakup of the Soviet Union, died Tuesday. He was 62.
</P>
<P>
   Elchibey, who was suffering from prostate cancer and a lung
infection, died in Gulhane Military hospital in Ankara, Turkey. He
was rushed unconscious to Turkey in July for medical treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Elchibey was elected president of the oil-rich Caucasus republic
in 1992 and set his country on a track of closer ties with Turkey,
a strong Western ally, irritating hard-liners in Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   But he was ousted from power after only a year by soldiers
enraged at their country's humiliating battlefield loses to
Armenians. Those defeats turned 1 million Azeris into refugees in
their own country, which borders Iran, Armenia and Russia.
</P>
<P>
   Armenian fighters drove Azeri forces from the disputed enclave
of Nagorno-Karabakh, a largely Armenian area within Azerbaijan, and
seized nearby areas of Azerbaijan proper. The fighting left 15,000
dead.
</P>
<P>
   Angry officers blamed Elchibey for the losses.
</P>
<P>
   Some 45,000 soldiers loyal to Surat Huseynov, a former army
colonel who was demoted by Elchibey, marched on the capital, Baku,
in 1993 and vowed to continue until Elchibey stepped down.
</P>
<P>
   Elchibey was replaced by Geidar Aliev, the former communist
leader of Azerbaijan, who remains president. Elchibey returned home
to Nakhichevan, an enclave cut off from Azerbaijan by Armenia.
</P>
<P>
   ''I felt great sorrow over Elchibey's death,'' Aliev said in a
televised message that was aired by Turkey's private NTV
television.
</P>
<P>
   Elchibey was born in Nakhichevan and taught Asian and African
history at Baku State University in the 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   In 1964 he formed an underground group to work for the
independence of Azerbaijan, which was soon forced to disband.
</P>
<P>
   In January 1975, Elchibey was tried on charges of anti-Soviet
activities and sentenced to 1&AMP;frac12; years in a labor camp in Azerbaijan.
</P>
<P>
   When he became president, Elchibey worked to eject all Russian
soldiers from the republic and tried to curb Iranian influence in
his country.
</P>
<P>
   Elchibey was close to Turkish nationalists who call for the
union of Turkic countries. Azerbaijan and Turkey share close ethnic
ties and the Azeri language is easily understood by Turks.
</P>
<P>
   ''He was a lover of the Turkic world,'' Turkish Prime Minister
Bulent Ecevit said. ''He was a valuable politician raised by
Azerbaijan.''
</P>
<P>
   Turkish politicians gathered at Ankara's airport for a moment of
silence and a brief military ceremony before Elchibey's body was
flown back to Baku.
</P>
<P>
   ''His body will be taken for a state funeral like a former
president deserves,'' said Azerbaijan's ambassador in Turkey, Memed
Aliev. ''Elchibey was a very honorable man.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
