<HEADLINE> Dow Jumps 107; Nasdaq adds 39  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks rose Tuesday after the Federal Reserve,
as expected, left interest rates unchanged, indicating inflation
fears are moderating.
</P>
<P>
   At late afternoon on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial
average was up 106.94 at 11,186.03.
</P>
<P>
   Broader stock indicators also were rising. The Nasdaq composite
index was up 38.53 at 3,991.68, the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index was
up 5.67 at 1,505.15.
</P>
<P>
   Big movers among the Dow industrials included Honeywell, up
$1.875 at $38.563, and J.P. Morgan, up $3.938 at $148.875. Both
companies would benefit if Fed officials are finished boosting
rates to fight inflation by slowing the economy.
</P>
<P>
   Most analysts had expected the Fed to leave rates alone as a
stream of economic data in recent weeks suggested the central bank
has succeeded in slowing the economy and keeping the lid on
inflation. The Fed had raised rates six times since June 1999,
before leaving them unchanged at its last policymaking meeting in
July.
</P>
<P>
   The Fed on Tuesday said it was maintaining its close watch on
inflation, however. The Fed's next meeting is in early October.
</P>
<P>
   ''We got exactly what we wanted,'' said Larry Wachtel, a market
analyst at Prudential Securities.
</P>
<P>
   The market had been rallying for the past month on the
expectation that the Fed would leave interest rates alone.
</P>
<P>
   Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a slender margin on
the New York Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Trading volume on the NYSE totaled 658.21 million shares, up
from 581.33 million at the same point on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies was up 1.08 at
518.25.
</P>
