<HEADLINE> Woodstock film festival to showcase independent film  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) - From short films to full-length features, more
than 60 movies will be showcased at the Woodstock Film Festival
next month, organizers announced Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the movies in the first-time festival, to be held Sept.
21-24 in the art community of Woodstock, N.Y., focus on music.
There's ''A Voice from Heaven,'' a documentary on Pakistani singer
Ustad Nusrat Fateh Ali Khan making its New York debut, and a dance
party to screen the 1984 Jonathan Demme music documentary, ''Stop
Making Sense.''
</P>
<P>
   The lineup for the festival was to be announced at a Tuesday
night news conference in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Other films cover a range of subjects, from ''That Creepy Old
Doll,'' a four-minute animated movie where a little girl celebrates
her birthday by scaring herself, to ''Black Milk,'' a feature where
the main character, a young writer, can transport himself in space
and time.
</P>
<P>
   ''Woodstock seemed to be the absolutely natural spot for an
independent film festival to take place,'' said director and
producer Meira Blaustein, who is orchestrating the festival with
her husband, film editor Laurent Rejto.
</P>
<P>
   ''There was nothing like that here,'' she said. ''On the other
hand, there are so many filmmakers and filmlovers that live right
in this area.''
</P>
<P>
   The festival will also include concerts and workshops. Workshops
will include adapting books to film and examining the impact of
digital production. Speakers include actor Aidan Quinn, author
Warren Adler and ''Philadelphia'' screenwriter Ron Nyswaner.
</P>
<P>
   Independent filmmaker Les Blank will be given a special Maverick
Award at the festival to honor his body of work, which has focused
on musicians and communities all over the United States. Other
Maverick Awards will be given in five categories: feature,
documentary, short, short documentary, and student film.
</P>
<P>
   ---
</P>
