<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-22 16:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Ambassador in Magazine Squabble  </HEADLINE>
By CAROLINE RNE
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON (AP) -- As diplomatic incidents go, the squabble between
Tatler magazine and the U.S. ambassador over his 15-year-old
daughter's article savaging British boys ranks decidedly lower than
any trade war.
</P>
<P>
   But the media storm that accompanied Mary-Catherine Lader's
indictment -- particularly over whether or not she maintained that
''British boys really suck'' -- threatens to turn her broadside into
an Anglo-American contretemps.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. ambassador Philip Lader fired off a letter to Tatler on
Aug. 11 accusing editors of manufacturing the ''British boys'' line
and inserting it in bold red letters even though Mary-Catherine
objected to it.
</P>
<P>
   The publication caused ''considerable embarrassment to my
daughter and our family,'' he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   ''Extensive publicity attendant to the publication of this
article has stemmed from, or been characterized by, language that
was not in her submitted draft and actually was suggested by an
adult editor,'' wrote Lader, who has been on vacation since the
August article appeared.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the society magazine has accused Lader of a little
sensationalism of his own. Tatler said that the ambassador's
letter, distributed by the embassy to news organizations, has yet
to arrive at its office.
</P>
<P>
   So far, nobody from the U.S. embassy has even called, said
Tatler editor Geordie Greig.
</P>
<P>
   ''Every paragraph, every word, every sentence was checked off by
her and she was 100 percent happy with it,'' said Greig, who added
that he sat in on the meeting with Mary-Catherine at which she
signed off on the final column.
</P>
<P>
   The girl's two-page opinion piece -- developed after she moved
from South Carolina to London in 1997 -- complained that British
boys are scrawny, pale, antisocial and sulking.
</P>
<P>
   ''At first I gave all the boys who had underwhelmed me the
benefit of the doubt but, after three years, I've finally
distinguished what it is -- that American guys have it and Brits
don't,'' the column said.
</P>
<P>
   Mary-Catherine, who attends St. Paul's Girls School, wasn't just
quibbling over personal style, however. British boys were called
''cheap,'' far too quick to make a pass and -- in short -- nothing to
write home about.
</P>
<P>
   ''Even most British girls I know admit that American guys beat
the English when it comes to looks,'' the column said.
</P>
<P>
   The British press, from The Times and The Daily Telegraph to The
Mirror and other tabloids, was quick to respond.
</P>
<P>
   ''I wasn't aware diplomatic bags came as young as 15,'' wrote
The Mirror's Bill Borrows. ''Perhaps she should pack up her Prada
bag (and) go back to the land of Jerry Springer.''
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, U.S. embassy spokesman Barry Levin reiterated that
the ambassador's daughter had not used the phrase ''sucks'' in her
original draft article, and that she had told editors it was not
something of which she would approve.
</P>
<P>
   ''The ambassador's letter speaks for itself,'' Levin said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Greig said Lader should be proud of his daughter's
''stunningly provocative'' journalistic debut.
</P>
<P>
   ''Newsstand sales are up 11 percent, which is terrific,'' he
said. ''I've just come back from the U.S. and she was very much the
talk of Manhattan.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-22-00 1653 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000822.0106 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-22 16:56 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 15 Cities Decry Virginia Census Law  </HEADLINE>
By GENARO C. ARMAS
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Fifteen cities and counties across the country
hope to join a legal fight against a Virginia state law barring the
use of statistically adjusted census data for political
redistricting.
</P>
<P>
   Virginia is one of 16 states covered under the federal Voting
Rights Act that must gain approval from the U.S. Justice Department
before changing affected state laws. In April, the state asked a
three-judge panel of U.S. District Court for the District of
Columbia to rule that the law requiring the use of nonsampled
numbers did not violate federal regulations and should not be
subject to Justice approval.
</P>
<P>
   The 15 cities and counties, led by Los Angeles, have asked the
court if they could ''intervene'' in the case on Justice's behalf.
They contend that the use of the statistical method known as
''sampling'' helps account for parts of the population missed in
prior counts, including minorities, the poor and inner-city
residents that tend to vote Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   The case is being closely watched by other states with similar
laws as a benchmark for deciding the constitutionality of sampled
data.
</P>
<P>
   ''Even though it's all taking place around Virginia's
redistricting requirement, if that kind of decision came down
(approving the law), it would affect the whole country,'' Jessica
Hines, assistant city attorney for Los Angeles, said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ''Virginia is obligated to move forward with swift, timely
elections for 2001,'' said David Botkins, spokesman for Virginia
Attorney General Mark Earley, a Republican. ''The census should be
a real count, not statistically adjusted data, which is nothing
more than guesswork.''
</P>
<P>
   Hines said Los Angeles and other cities and counties concerned
with the case all suffered undercounts in the last census in 1990.
They include: Richmond, Va.; Houston; Denver; Inglewood, Calif.;
Oakland; San Francisco; San Antonio; Dearborn, Mich.; and Dade
County, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   ''Cities have a distinct interest in the sampling debate,'' said
Gerry Hebert, a lawyer representing several Virginia state
legislators who intervened in the case against the law. ''A lot of
the outcome is in the inner city, where minorities have been
underrepresented.''
</P>
<P>
   Census figures are used to reapportion billions of federal
dollars among the states. The Constitution also calls for census
data to be used every 10 years to reapportion the 435 House seats
among states, and to redraw political district lines within states.
</P>
<P>
   Raw census data is due to be released by Dec. 31; sampled
numbers by April 1.
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court last year said that reapportionment must be
based solely on raw population totals. It left open to states the
option of using either set of numbers for redistricting,
heightening the importance of statehouse elections in the years to
come.
</P>
<P>
   ''What's important is that everybody be counted and the most
accurate, responsible way to do that is through an actual head
count,'' Botkins said.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: Census Bureau site: http://www.census.gov/
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
