<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Myanmar Rulers Control Students  </HEADLINE>
By VIJAY JOSHI
<TEXT>
<P>
   BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) -- Myanmar's military rulers have reopened
the country's universities after 3&AMP;frac12; years, but are keeping students
under tight control by making them pledge their loyalty to the
government and barring political activity, said pro-democracy
leader Aung San Suu Kyi.
</P>
<P>
   The reopening of the universities ''is a mere surface job to
make people think that there has been progress'' on democratic
rights in Myanmar, the Nobel Peace Prize winner said in a
videotaped statement smuggled out of the country by human rights
activists and shown to reporters in Bangkok on Tuesday. ''But in
fact there has been no progress.''
</P>
<P>
   Myanmar's rulers allowed full resumption of higher education on
July 24. They closed down campuses to stop anti-government
demonstrations in December 1996.
</P>
<P>
   The 14 activists, who included academics, journalists, youth
workers and students from 10 countries, joined 200 Suu Kyi
supporters at a workshop Monday in the Myanmar capital of Yangon to
discuss the state of education in the country, also known as Burma.
</P>
<P>
   The workshop was held at the headquarters of Suu Kyi's
opposition party, the National League for Democracy, whose
activities are kept under close scrutiny by the government,
especially when they involve foreign visitors and journalists.
</P>
<P>
   The party won general elections in 1990, but the military regime
never allowed it to form a government. Suu Kyi won the 1991 Nobel
Peace prize.
</P>
<P>
   Activists said the government did not try to disrupt the
workshop, but security officials at the airport searched them and
confiscated one videotape, not realizing it was blank.
</P>
<P>
   Students have been politically active in Myanmar since the days
of British colonial rule earlier this century. They spearheaded an
uprising that almost toppled the military in 1988. Thousands of
protesters were gunned down.
</P>
<P>
   Students were being allowed to enroll after signing a
declaration that they will stay away from political activities and
be loyal to the government. Student unions and other student
organizations are banned.
</P>
<P>
   ''Education is a conditionality, not a right in Myanmar,'' said
Christine Weima Lager, a youth worker from Norway. ''If you want
education you have to give up your political rights.''
</P>
<P>
   Lager and the other activists said political science is not a
subject in the universities.
</P>
<P>
   Suu Kyi urged student movements around the world to force their
governments to pressure Myanmar's rulers into freeing the campuses.
</P>
<P>
   ''We would like ... the student community to think of education
in Burma as part of our broader political problem,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-22-00 1659 </TRAILER>
