<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-22 17:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Syria-Israel Talks Not Revived  </HEADLINE>
By BARRY SCHWEID
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Syria remains interested in making peace with
Israel, but after another overture by Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright a way to revive stalled talks has not been found, the
State Department said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Negotiations sponsored by the Clinton administration broke down
in January. Albright telephoned Foreign Minister Farouk al-Sharaa
on Monday in an attempt to reopen them.
</P>
<P>
   ''The door has remained open to progress along this track, but
at this point we don't have anything specific to report on
restarting,'' the State Department spokesman Richard Boucher said.
</P>
<P>
   Parallel efforts are being made in the region by senior U.S.
mediator Dennis B. Ross. His main goal is to prod Israel and the
Palestinians into a settlement, but there, too, American diplomacy
is hitting a brick wall.
</P>
<P>
   The late Syrian President Hafez Assad declared peace with Israel
was in Syria's strategic interest. Consequently, he demanded
surrender of the strategic Golan Heights border enclave, which
Syria lost in the 1967 Mideast war, as well as a strip of shore
along the Sea of Galilee. His son and successor, Bashar Ashad, is
committed to the same demands.
</P>
<P>
   According to reports from Damascus, Foreign Minister al-Sharaa
reiterated those demands in his telephone conversation with
Albright.
</P>
<P>
   She also has talked twice to Foreign Minister Hubert Vedrine of
France in the last week and to Foreign Minister Amr Moussa of Egypt
on Monday, looking for ''ways to move the process forward,''
Boucher said.
</P>
<P>
   ''She has stayed actively engaged with regional leaders,'' the
spokesman said. ''We believe that both the Syrians and the Israelis
want to reach an agreement.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
