<HEADLINE> Clinton and Lazio continue debate over debates  </HEADLINE>
With BC-NY--NY Senate, Bjt
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - Rick Lazio's Senate campaign on Tuesday said
Hillary Rodham Clinton was ducking debates, a charge denied by the
first lady's campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Noting that Clinton has said she is willing to debate the
congressman from Long Island ''anytime, anywhere,'' Lazio campaign
manager Bill Dal Col said she has only agreed to one of three
debates her Republican rival has accepted.
</P>
<P>
   ''She apparently has her own version of Clinton-speak where
'anytime, anywhere' means sometime, somewhere, maybe, I'll decide
later,'' Dal Col said.
</P>
<P>
   The Lazio campaign said that while it had agreed to a debate in
Buffalo on Sept. 13, moderated by NBC's Tim Russert, and two more
later in New York City, Clinton had agreed to only the Buffalo
debate thus far.
</P>
<P>
   ''That is a total lie,'' Clinton spokesman Howard Wolfson said.
</P>
<P>
   Wolfson said the first lady had agreed to the Buffalo debate and
was in the process of finalizing dates for the other two.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio campaign spokesman Dan McLagan said that while the first
lady has agreed to the Buffalo debate on Sept. 13, she has yet to
agree to dates proposed for the other two debates, Sept. 24 on
WCBS-TV and Oct. 18 on WNBC-TV.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're trying to pin them down,'' McLagan said.
</P>
<P>
   Wolfson noted that the first lady has also accepted an
invitation from WABC-TV and the League of Women Voters for a fourth
debate. McLagan said that was still under consideration by the
Lazio camp.
</P>
<P>
   Wolfson, noting Clinton had accepted two other proposed debates
that Lazio hadn't agreed to, said, ''Rick Lazio should stop ducking
and accept all the debates that Hillary has agreed to.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lazio campaign, meanwhile, noted that the congressman had
unsuccessfully offered to debate the first lady on Russert's ''Meet
the Press'' show on July 30.
</P>
</TEXT>
