<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-22 17:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Horse owners urged to vaccinate their animals against encephalitis  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - Eastern equine encephalitis is being blamed
for causing the death of a quarter horse in Newfield, Gloucester
County, and horse owners are being urged to ensure their animals
have been vaccinated.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Ernest Zirkle, the state veterinarian, said the horse that
was put down last Wednesday had not been vaccinated.
</P>
<P>
   Zirkle said Eastern equine encephalitis should not be confused
with West Nile virus, the potentially fatal virus that killed seven
people in New York and sickened dozens last year. Three Staten
Island residents in New York have tested positive for the virus
this year.
</P>
<P>
   ''They are completely different diseases but share some
characteristics - in both cases mosquitoes carry the virus to the
host animal after feeding on infected wild birds,'' Zirkle said in
a prepared statement. ''Neither virus can be spread from horse to
horse or from horse to human.''
</P>
<P>
   Zirkle noted there is no vaccine for West Nile virus.
</P>
<P>
   ''Horse owners should check their records to make sure that EEE
vaccinations and boosters are kept up to date,'' he said. ''Any
horse that hasn't received a primary series or booster within the
last six months should be given the vaccination or booster now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
