<HEADLINE> Bird-biting mosquitoes found in Norwalk, 26 more dead crows discovered </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) - Bird-biting mosquitoes infected with the
West Nile virus have turned up again in Norwalk, but state
officials said Tuesday they do not plan any new pesticide spraying
as a result.
</P>
<P>
   The mosquitoes, of the culex restuans variety, were collected
Aug. 7 at the Rowayton School trap site in Norwalk.
</P>
<P>
   ''West Nile virus activity has intensified over the past several
weeks and isolation of the virus in another mosquito pool does not
come as a surprise,'' said Department of Environmental Protection
Commissioner Arthur J. Rocque.
</P>
<P>
   Officials on Tuesday also announced the discovery of 26
additional crows infected with the virus, collected in Darien,
Milford, New Canaan, Norwalk, Stamford, Wallingford, West Hartford
and Wethersfield.
</P>
<P>
   ''The state's program has identified West Nile Virus birds in 19
communities and expects to identify it in many more,'' Rocque said.
</P>
<P>
   The virus first surfaced in the region last year, killing seven
people - all of whom were over 75 - and sickening 62 others in New
York. It also killed hundreds of birds in Connecticut, New York and
New Jersey. There have been three human cases reported in New York
this year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
