<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-22 17:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Grains, Soybeans End Mostly Lower  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO (AP) -- Grain and soybean prices finished mostly lower
Tuesday after a day of sluggish trading on the Chicago Board of
Trade.
</P>
<P>
   Soybeans dipped on the outlook for crop-beneficial rains in the
Midwest and the prospect of showers in the Delta later in the week.
The weather overcame an early increase in the price based on a
slightly lower weekly crop rating issued by the U.S. Department of
Agriculture.
</P>
<P>
   Corn finished down slightly after also reversing course. Traders
said the crop rating decline wasn't enough to justify pushing
prices higher.
</P>
<P>
   Wheat fell under pressure from soybeans in a generally quiet
session.
</P>
<P>
   Wheat for December delivery fell 1&AMP;frac12; cent to $2.53 a bushel;
December corn fell &AMP;frac34; cent to $1.88 a bushel; December oats rose &AMP;frac34;
cent to $1.09&AMP;frac14; a bushel; November soybeans fell 3&AMP;frac34; cents to
$4.67&AMP;frac12;
a bushel.
</P>
<P>
   Beef futures finished mixed on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange,
while pork futures declined.
</P>
<P>
   October live cattle rose .07 cent to 68.22 cents a pound;
October feeder cattle fell .30 cent to 86.75 cents a pound; October
lean hogs fell 1.10 cent to 52.45 cents a pound; February frozen
pork bellies fell .38 cent to 65.02 cents a pound.
</P>
