<HEADLINE> Publishers Clearing House to change promotions, repay $18 million  </HEADLINE>
By SAMUEL MAULL
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - Publishers Clearing House has agreed to pay 24
states and the District of Columbia $18 million to settle lawsuits
that accused the sweepstakes promoter of deceptive marketing.
</P>
<P>
   State Attorney General Eliot Spitzer said on Tuesday that
Publishers Clearing House will refund money to thousands of
consumers and revise its methods of selling magazines, compact
discs, and other items through the mail.
</P>
<P>
   Consumers who received the company's 100 million mailings a year
included many elderly people who were victimized by its ''tricks,
gimmicks and greed,'' Spitzer said. He said the company sent some
of them 150 mailings a year.
</P>
<P>
   Among Publishers Clearing House's most famous ''gimmicks'' are
the garish envelopes sent to consumers in every state, saying ''You
May Have Already Won'' some prize and containing a simulated but
worthless check for a large amount of money.
</P>
<P>
   In reality, Spitzer said, the consumer had won nothing.
</P>
<P>
   ''People should know they have about as much chance of winning
these sweepstakes as they do of getting hit by lightning,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Spitzer said $1.6 million of the $18 million will go to 1,600
New Yorkers, most of them customers who spent at least $2,500 a
year with the company between 1997 and 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The attorney general's office will determine how much money each
individual gets based on a formula yet to be determined, Spitzer
said. He added that his office will receive $148,000 for the costs
of the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement also requires Publishers Clearing House to include
a ''sweepstakes fact box,'' similar to a nutrition content label,
in future mailings, Spitzer said.
</P>
<P>
   The box must say customers may enter for free, that buying won't
improve chances of winning, that customers may enter as often as
they like, that they have not yet won, and that all entries have
the same chance to win.
</P>
<P>
   ''The only reason someone should buy a magazine subscription,''
Spitzer said, ''is because they like the magazine. There is no link
between what you spend and your odds of winning anything.''
</P>
<P>
   In a statement about the settlement, Publishers Clearing House
said it has been in business 46 years and has awarded almost $160
million in prizes. The company said 24 of the 31 people who have
won $1 million or more did not buy anything when they sent in their
winning entries.
</P>
<P>
   Christopher L. Irving, senior director of consumer and legal
affairs at Publishers Clearing House, said the company has agreed
to contact consumers who spend more than $2,500 in a year with his
company.
</P>
<P>
   If consumers are confused about the sweepstakes' rules or about
their chances of winning, or if consumers are having money
troubles, they will be removed from the company's mailing list,
Irving said.
</P>
<P>
   Irving praised the agreement and said it should serve as a model
for other deals that Publishers Clearing House is trying to work
out with more than 20 other states that have filed lawsuits against
the company.
</P>
<P>
   ''There is no admission of wrongdoing by Publishers Clearing
House in this agreement,'' Irving said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-08-22-00 1737 </TRAILER>
