<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-22 17:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Camden leaders want state to help, not take over, ailing city  </HEADLINE>
By BRENDAN SCHURR
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMDEN, N.J. (AP) - The City Council wants the mayor, who has
been charged with extortion and money laundering, to resign. The
city attorney has quit, saying Council has created a ''hostile,
racist'' workplace. The business administrator is right behind him,
and Council members are forbidden by the mayor from speaking
directly with department heads.
</P>
<P>
   Things are difficult, to say the least, in Camden.
</P>
<P>
   The Whitman administration wants the state to have the power to
take over operations of New Jersey's poorest city. But city leaders
say they need cooperation, not control.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's against everything we've ever learned about democracy,''
Councilman Gilbert ''Whip'' Wilson said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   If the state were to take control, that would, in effect, seize
the citizens' voting rights, because the people they elected would
not be running the city, Wilson said.
</P>
<P>
   ''That's not the way it's supposed to work, not in this country
anyway. It's offensive, when you think of all the things done over
the years to keep freedom ringing - wars, the civil rights
movement. That's very precious to a lot of us, the right to vote.
Once you appoint an overseer, you have no rights.''
</P>
<P>
   But state officials said it's exactly the opposite.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's our belief that the residents might not be being served
now by that same democracy,'' Anthony Cancro, deputy commissioner
of the state Department of Community Affairs, said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   He said the state wants to ''give the people a voice by
providing more involvement and leadership that's not there now.''
</P>
<P>
   The state has been monitoring the city's spending and hiring
since May. But Gov. Christie Whitman wants the state to have the
authority to assume control of city operations. If that happens,
Camden would become the first New Jersey city to be fully run by
state government.
</P>
<P>
   A bill to give the state that power was introduced in the Senate
before the summer recess and no committee hearing is scheduled. No
action has been taken in the Assembly.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're unable to make the long, lasting changes we need without
this legislation,'' said Ulrich ''Al'' Steinberg, director of the
state Division of Local Government Services, which oversees city
operations.
</P>
<P>
   ''Over the last two or three decades, there's been Band-Aids put
on the problems in Camden. Our intent is really to address the long
term,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Steinberg also said trying to solve the problems without the
state's help would be limiting the resources available to
revitalize the city.
</P>
<P>
   ''To say they are able to turn around decades of problems
without the tools available at the state, I think, is looking at
things short term again,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Cancro said under the proposal, the state could reorganize city
departments to make them more efficient.
</P>
<P>
   ''We want to make sure the services the government is supposed
to provide are provided effectively and efficiently,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Also under the current system, we don't really have a sense of
a mayor that's responding to a leadership position,'' Cancro said.
''He hasn't been seen in a while.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the proposed legislation, a chief management officer would
be installed to ''provide some leadership and management skills in
the city, independent of politics,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   City Council on Friday unanimously voted to ask Mayor Milton
Milan to step down. Milan called the move a ''political gesture''
and defended his work as mayor.
</P>
<P>
   Milan has been indicted on federal charges of corruption and
money laundering. His trial is to begin in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   City attorney John A. Misci Jr. resigned last week, saying the
Council had created an ''unhealthy, openly hostile, racist and
retaliatory workplace.''
</P>
<P>
   Adding to the difficulties in City Hall, Milan recently directed
city department heads not to talk to Council members. Instead,
Council members must go through Business Administrator Preston
Taylor.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor, too, announced last week that he is resigning, effective
Oct. 31. Cancro said the state is working with city officials to
find a replacement.
</P>
<P>
   ''It stinks, this whole thing,'' Joseph A. Twardy, who owns a
tobacco shop across the street from City Hall, said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Twardy supports the state assuming control, saying ''anything
would be better than what's happening now.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Milton Milan thinks he's in Disney World,'' said Twardy. ''He
runs this here city the way Mickey Mouse would run it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-08-22-00 1743 </TRAILER>
