<HEADLINE> Stamford wins battle for combined IP-Champion HQ  </HEADLINE>
By DENISE LAVOIE
<TEXT>
<P>
   STAMFORD, Conn. (AP) - International Paper Co., which bought
Champion International Corp. in June, has agreed to move its
combined world headquarters from Purchase, N.Y., to Stamford.
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut officials and a spokesman for International Paper
said a verbal agreement was reached after Connecticut economic
development officials offered a generous package of incentives.
</P>
<P>
   The decision ends a fierce competition between Connecticut and
New York for IP, the top forest paper company in the world. For a
while, it looked like IP would keep the combined headquarters in
Purchase, where the company has been located since 1986.
</P>
<P>
   But Connecticut officials put on a full-court press to lure the
company to Stamford.
</P>
<P>
   International Paper will move its employees at its current
headquarters in Purchase to the building in downtown Stamford where
Champion had its headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut's Department of Economic &AMP; Community Development has
agreed to give IP a $1 million loan that will be forgiven after 10
years if the company retains 550 jobs in Connecticut. The jobs are
not limited to the Stamford headquarters, but can be anywhere in
Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   International Paper already employs about 430 people in
Connecticut in manufacturing operations in Waterbury and Putnam; an
office in East Granby; and a distribution network in West Haven,
Hartford and Stamford. The 120 IP workers to be moved from the
Purchase headquarters will bring the company up to the 550 required
under the loan.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the Connecticut Development Authority has agreed to
give the company a sales tax exemption for construction costs.
</P>
<P>
   The CDA has also agreed to give the owner of the Champion
building where the newly combined company will be located a $5.2
million loan for high-tech communications wiring and other
improvements.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a real feather in the cap for Connecticut,'' said James
Watson, a spokesman for the Department of Economic &AMP; Community
Development.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Cox, a spokesman for IP, said the company wanted to move
its headquarters from its current location in a suburban office
park.
</P>
<P>
   ''While (the financial package offered by Connecticut) was a
considerable part of the decision, one of the real motivating
factors was the visibility we would have as a corporation in
Stamford,'' said Cox.
</P>
<P>
   Stamford is home to several major corporations, including Xerox
Corp., Pitney Bowes and GE Capital.
</P>
<P>
   Champion, with $5.3 billion in revenues and about 17,000
employees, was acquired in June by the much-larger IP, with $24.6
billion in revenues and about 100,000 employees.
</P>
<P>
   Cox said it is still unclear how many people will end up working
at the combined headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   About 120 people currently work at IP's headquarters in
Purchase. Cox said all of those employees have been offered jobs at
the new headquarters, which is roughly 12 miles from the Purchase
location.
</P>
<P>
   Before the acquisition, Champion had about 375 employees at its
Stamford headquarters. About 265 of those employees have been given
notices that their jobs will be eliminated. Another 50 have been
given jobs with IP, although most of them are going to be
transferred to other locations.
</P>
<P>
   Cox said the fate of the remaining 60 Champion employees is
unclear because IP is continuing to integrate the two businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Watson said he expects a formal agreement to be signed within
the next two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a done deal,'' said Cox, who said the company hopes to
complete the move by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Stamford Mayor Dannel Malloy, who was involved in the
negotiations, said there was an intense competition between the two
states.
</P>
<P>
   ''Quite frankly, I thought they were going to New York. At any
number of times, I thought we had lost, but we kept at the table
and kept the lines of communication open.''
</P>
<P>
   New York officials said they also offered IP incentives to stay
in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ''We put forth a competitive offer ... but it was difficult to
compete against a building they now own in Stamford,'' said Charles
Gargano, chairman and chief executive of Empire State Development,
the economic arm of New York state.
</P>
<P>
   ''We don't like to lose any jobs but ... the good news is that
that area of Westchester County ... there is an influx of
information technology and telecommunications expansions. We have
every confidence that the (IP) space will be filled.''
</P>
</TEXT>
