<HEADLINE> An analysis of Clinton ad criticizing Lazio's legislative record  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated Press	   An analysis of the new Clinton campaign ad regarding
Republican
Senate candidate Rick Lazio's congressional record:
<TEXT>
<P>
   TITLE: ''Won't See''
</P>
<P>
   LENGTH: 30 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCERS: Mandy Grunwald, Mark Penn and DeVito/Verdi agency.
</P>
<P>
   AIRING: Statewide beginning Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   SCRIPT: (Read by a male announcer)
</P>
<P>
   ''The end to nursing home standards. The largest education cuts
in history. The slashing of Medicare by $270 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
   ''Who voted for all this? Rick Lazio.
</P>
<P>
   ''Four years as Newt Gingrich's deputy whip. You won't see that
in his ads.
</P>
<P>
   ''And you won't see his recent votes against investing in
100,000 new teachers, and against guaranteed prescription drug
coverage under Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   ''With Rick Lazio, the more you know, the more you wonder.''
</P>
<P>
   IMAGES: Black background, white letters with the title of each
act appearing as it's read. As the announcer mentions Gingrich, a
still picture of Lazio and the former speaker of the House appears
on screen, followed by a headshot of Lazio that accompanies the
ad's final words.
</P>
<P>
   ANALYSIS: The spot visually resembles an ad Lazio's campaign put
out recently with the titles of various pieces of legislation he
supports appearing on screen.
</P>
<P>
   Both commercials are seriously focused on the issues - not on
personalities - though Lazio's campaign has taken such ads
personally in the past.
</P>
<P>
   This one is designed to draw attention to Lazio's sometimes more
conservative stance on legislative issues, which he has recently
tried to cast himself as moderate on.
</P>
<P>
   This summer, for example, he was the only New York Republican to
vote against a $352 billion bill funding education, health and
human services. Democrats said the bill cut the programs too
deeply. It was the first time Lazio voted with Democrats on such a
bill.
</P>
<P>
   Many New Yorkers are heavily dependent on social services, and
the state gets a huge amount of federal dollars from the programs.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton campaign manager Bill de Blasio said the issues
Clinton's most recent ad takes on - support for nursing home
standards, education, and Medicare - are ones crucial to New York.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is what the debate should be about, what did you vote
for, what did you vote against?'' de Blasio said.
</P>
<P>
   There is a certain slight-of-hand to the ad, however. It
criticizes Lazio for voting against a prescription drug benefit for
Medicare recipients. In truth, he has also supported such coverage
as part of a Republican-backed plan the Clinton ad doesn't mention.
</P>
<P>
   ''To say he voted against coverage is not accurate. He voted for
another plan,'' said Lazio campaign spokesman Bryan Flood.
</P>
<P>
   ---
</P>
<P>
   Analysis by Sharon L. Crenson, Associated Press Writer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-08-22-00 1815 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
