<BODY>
<HEADLINE> President to visit overcrowded school, attend two fund-raisers  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated Press	   President Clinton will visit an overcrowded school
district to
speak about school construction and attend two fund-raisers for New
Jersey congressional candidates in the state on Wednesday.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Clinton will meet with students and teachers at the Crossroads
Middle School in South Brunswick, where more than 200 of the
school's 1,635 sixth-, seventh- and eighth-grade students attend
class in trailers scattered around campus.
</P>
<P>
   ''We can't build them fast enough,'' South Brunswick Assistant
Superintendent Willa Spicer said of new schools.
</P>
<P>
   The district of over 7,000 students has grown by about 400
children a year for the past seven or eight years, she said.
Twenty-one trailers make up classrooms at Crossroads and two other
schools in the district, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Spicer said the central New Jersey city is becoming increasingly
popular for parents with diverse commuting needs.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's halfway between New York and Philadelphia,'' she said.
''It's halfway between Rutgers and Princeton. It's on a train line,
it's on the turnpike.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton will also headline fund-raisers in Princeton and Cherry
Hill later Wednesday for U.S. Rep. Rush Holt, D-Pennington, and
Cherry Hill Mayor Susan Bass Levin.
</P>
<P>
   The president will speak at a $1,000-a-head fund-raiser at a
Princeton private home for Holt, D-Pennington, who is seeking
re-election against former Rep. Dick Zimmer.
</P>
<P>
   Levin, who is in her first congressional race against Republican
Rep. James Saxton, expects at least 400 people at the $300-a-head
cocktail reception at Garden State Park in Cherry Hill.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
