<HEADLINE> Dow Ends Up 59; Nasdaq Rises 5  </HEADLINE>
By PHIL GALEWITZ
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Blue chip stocks rose Tuesday after the Federal
Reserve kept interest rates unchanged, indicating inflation fears
are moderating. Technology stocks were mixed, with computer shares
up and telecommunications issues down, partly on worries of slowing
corporate profits.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average gained 59.34 at 11,139.15.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq composite index rose 5.06 at 3,958.21 and the
Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index slipped 1.35 at 1,498.13.
</P>
<P>
   Market watchers had expected the Fed to leave rates steady as a
stream of economic data in recent weeks suggested the economy was
slowing and inflation was under control. The Fed had raised rates
six times since last summer in an effort to bring the fast moving
economic expansion in for a soft landing.
</P>
<P>
   While the Fed on Tuesday said it was maintaining its close watch
on inflation, it noted that ''rapid advances in productivity have
been raising the potential growth rate'' of the economy. That
bullish statement was missing from the Fed's June statement when it
also left rates unchanged.
</P>
<P>
   Various economists cited these more positive comments to bolster
their positions that the Fed has finished raising rates. The Fed's
next meeting is in early October.
</P>
<P>
   ''We got exactly what we wanted,'' said Larry Wachtel, a market
analyst at Prudential Securities.
</P>
<P>
   The market had been rallying for the past month on the
expectation that the Fed would leave interest rates alone. But a
more sluggish economy also raised the specter of slowing corporate
profits which could hurt stocks, particularly more risky technology
shares.
</P>
<P>
   Most banking and retail stocks rose on the Fed's decision, with
PNC Financial jumping $2 to $59.125 and the Gap, adding $1.25 to
$28.375.
</P>
<P>
   In the tech sectors, most software and computer stocks gained,
while investors sold semiconductor and telecommunications issues.
</P>
<P>
   Computer maker Gateway added 75 cents to $63 and software
designer Adobe Systems rose $2.375 to $122.25. Sprint PCS was the
biggest decliner among telecom stocks, falling $3.188 to $49.
</P>
<P>
   Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a slender margin on
the New York Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Composite volume on the NYSE totaled 1.01 billion shares, up
from 909.05 million Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies was up 1.01 at
517.46.
</P>
<P>
   Overseas, Japan's Nikkei stock average rose 2.58 percent,
Germany's DAX index was up 0.69 percent, Britain's FT-SE 100 was up
0.65 percent, and France's CAC-40 was down 0.88 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   New York Stock Exchange: http://www.nyse.com
</P>
<P>
   Nasdaq Stock Market: http://www.nasdaq.com
</P>
</TEXT>
