<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-22 18:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Latest trooper recruits still mostly white males  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN P. McALPIN
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - Despite a recruiting drive that targeted
minorities and a revamped testing process, the latest pool of
potential New Jersey state troopers is still mostly white and
virtually all male.
</P>
<P>
   Many minorities distrust the State Police and law enforcement in
general, a disappointed Superintendent Col. Carson Dunbar said
Tuesday as he announced the results of the recruiting process.
</P>
<P>
   The State Police must combat that fear as well as a booming
economy to attract more minorities and women, Dunbar said.
</P>
<P>
   Dunbar said he has worked to diversify the ranks, but those
efforts are still not working. After charges of racial profiling
became widely public many criticized the State Police for being
mostly white with few minority supervisors.
</P>
<P>
   ''Out of all the problems that I face, this may be one of the
most difficult that I deal with,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Several times Dunbar admitted that the figures he made public
were not the ones he had hoped for.
</P>
<P>
   About 14 percent of the 3,000 troopers are minorities and 3
percent are women.
</P>
<P>
   Only one woman is in the final pool of 105 candidates.
Minorities account for about 14 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ''When I started off, I thought these numbers would be better,''
Dunbar said. ''It is very difficult to attract individuals to law
enforcement.''
</P>
<P>
   Just over 5,000 people applied for the job, according to state
police figures. Of those approximately 86 percent were males and 30
percent were minorities.
</P>
<P>
   After each step in the testing process, the percentages of
females and minority applicants dropped.
</P>
<P>
   ''As we went through this, proportionately we kept losing
people, which is to be expected,'' Dunbar said.
</P>
<P>
   Critics faulted the State Police for not keeping track of
applicants who do not return after each testing level.
</P>
<P>
   After settling a lawsuit with the NAACP in March, the state
agreed to allow former applicants to reapply. Dunbar said that
applicants were also personally screened if they were rejected
after an interview.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time, trooper candidates were interviewed by
people outside the department, Dunbar said. The panel included a
human resources expert from another area of state government and at
least one minority, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The screening process was different from the beginning,
according to Dunbar.
</P>
<P>
   Each application was reviewed by someone who did not know the
race or gender of the applicant. Physical fitness standards changed
and applicants were allowed to take that test up to four times.
</P>
<P>
   But Dunbar said that does not mean standards were lowered to
allow more minorities and women to pass.
</P>
<P>
   ''Once the testing process starts, then I think my
responsibility is to be fair,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Assemblyman LeRoy J. Jones, D-Essex, said he is concerned by
what he called a failure to diversify the ranks of the State
Police.
</P>
<P>
   ''Clearly they need to reassess their approach and re-examine
who they are using as consultants in recruiting minorities into the
ranks,'' Jones said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   When recruits begin classes Sept. 5, they will see more changes.
</P>
<P>
   The previous class numbered 175 cadets. Dunbar said cadet
classes will now be no larger than 50. That comes after
consultation with other police groups, including the Royal Canadian
Mounted Police.
</P>
<P>
   ''All of them have seen that smaller is better and we're going
to follow that,'' Dunbar said.
</P>
<P>
   Cadets will also be issued laptop computers and be allowed to
work shorter days. They will also be scheduled to attend classes in
night shifts, much like troopers assigned to road duty, Dunbar
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
