<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hillary Clinton campaigns for women's votes  </HEADLINE>
By CAROLYN THOMPSON
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROCHESTER, N.Y. (AP) - Hillary Clinton visited the birthplace of
the suffrage movement Tuesday to stress her credentials on women's
issues, including abortion, and attack those of her U.S. Senate
opponent, Rick Lazio.
</P>
<P>
   During a visit to Rochester that took her to a shopping mall,
women's gathering and the Susan B. Anthony House, Clinton sought to
reach women voters who, according to polls, have been inconsistent
in their support.
</P>
<P>
   Continuing her compare-and-contrast strategy, Clinton repeated
her promise never to vote to confirm any U.S. Supreme Court nominee
who would vote to overturn Roe vs. Wade, and attacked Lazio for
refusing to make the same pledge.
</P>
<P>
   ''He has already voted against ... funding for poor women,
voting to prohibit American women in the military from using their
own funds,'' she told supporters at an event with U.S. Rep. Louise
Slaughter, D-N.Y., where she also cited the need for improved child
health care and education, higher standards for nursing homes, tax
credits for long-term care providers and more money for breast
cancer research.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio ''has a very anti-choice record,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   While both candidates say they are abortion rights supporters,
Lazio is opposed to using federal Medicaid funds to pay for poor
women's abortions and favors a ban on what critics call
''partial-birth abortion.'' Clinton favors Medicaid funding and is
opposed to a partial-birth abortion ban.
</P>
<P>
   At the gathering, 99-year-old Ruth Dyk told of marching with
suffragettes in Boston. ''If I have learned one thing,'' she said,
''it is that New York needs a woman's touch.''
</P>
<P>
   Such direct appeals to women voters will position the first lady
to provide that touch, Slaughter predicted.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think she'll benefit a great deal just by being here
today,'' the congresswoman said after the women were given a
room-by-room tour of the Susan B. Anthony House, the former
headquarters for the National American Woman Suffrage Association
and the site of Anthony's arrest for voting in 1872.
</P>
<P>
   After the tour, Clinton added her name to a petition advocating
a U.S. stamp for Martha Matilda Harper, who is credited with
creating modern franchising by opening a chain of beauty salons in
Rochester. The first lady also promised to call on a friend at the
Harvard Business School to see about adding Harper's
accomplishments to the curriculum.
</P>
<P>
   The most recent polls show women backing Clinton over Lazio, 50
percent to 38 percent. But among white women, Clinton has
consistently trailed - 41 percent to 46 percent in an August poll
by Quinnipiac University Polling Institute. Interviews have shown
that some in the crucial voting bloc resent what they see as her
riding her husband's coattails. Others believe she should not have
stuck with the president in light of his infidelities.
</P>
<P>
   Sherry Shaw, who waited at the Marketplace mall to shake
Clinton's hand, said she viewed the first lady's commitment to her
marriage as a plus.
</P>
<P>
   ''She showed incredible strength in standing by him. In my mind,
it's not a weakness, it's a strength,'' she said. ''She certainly
has put her family first. That's family values right there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
