<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cape May-Lewes Ferry continues to sell food despite third inspection failure </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   LOWER TOWNSHIP, N.J. (AP) - The operators of the Cape May-Lewes
Ferry will continue to sell prepared food despite being told to
stop by the U.S. Food and Drug Administration.
</P>
<P>
   The directive came in an Aug. 18 letter from FDA District
Director Douglas Ellsworth to the Delaware River and Bay Authority,
which operates the ferries.
</P>
<P>
   The letter was sent after four of the fleet's five ships failed
a third round of health inspections Aug. 10-12. Ellsworth noted
that the authority has made improvements but ''the conditions under
which food is stored, handled, prepared and served remain
unsanitary,'' he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the findings, the authority will continue to cook up
hamburgers, hot dogs, french fries and other fast food for
passengers, said James Salmon, a spokesman for the authority.
</P>
<P>
   ''We believe the authority's food service operation is safe,
clean and professionally managed,'' Salmon said.
</P>
<P>
   Salmon said food service standards were being improved and that
a new corrective-action plan, filed Tuesday, would address some of
FDA's complaints. The authority had until Friday to file a plan.
</P>
<P>
   The authority has spent $13,000 on new equipment and held
training sessions for 160 food service employees, Salmon said.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 70 percent of the ferries' 1.3 million annual passengers
snack on the prepared foods during their excursions, Salmon said.
</P>
<P>
   The FDA has classified the ferry food service as
''use-prohibited,'' meaning the authority should not prepare, serve
or sell any food that requires ''manual manipulation of
ingredients,'' Ellsworth wrote.
</P>
<P>
   The FDA can take measures to seize all food or shut down food
service if the authority continues to prepare and serve food while
it is use-prohibited.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
