<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-22 18:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Law imposes tougher murder sentences when death penalty involved  </HEADLINE>
By AMY WESTFELDT
<TEXT>
<P>
   LODI, N.J. (AP) - A law prompted by the parole bids of a
murderer of two Lodi police officers ensures that convicted
murderers who face the death penalty will at least serve life in
prison without parole, lawmakers said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The bill signed into law by Acting Governor Donald DiFrancesco
in front of the relatives of the two slain officers, however, does
not affect the case of Thomas Trantino, who faces a state Supreme
Court hearing next month on a judge's order to parole him.
</P>
<P>
   ''We know this initiative will not undo the damage that was done
at the hands of this particular murderer,'' DiFrancesco said of
Trantino. ''We can, however, ensure their families and the families
of all victims of crime that they won't have to relive their pain
through the parole process.''
</P>
<P>
   The new law states that in cases where prosecutors seek the
death penalty for convicted murderers, the defendants must serve no
less than life without parole. Under the previous law, judges could
sentence murderers to 30 years to life in prison with the
possibility of parole if juries decline to issue a death sentence
or if the defendant's death sentence is overturned.
</P>
<P>
   Trantino was sentenced to die for killing officers Gary Tedesco
and Peter Voto in a bar in August 1963. But when New Jersey's death
penalty was overturned in 1972, Trantino's sentence was changed to
life in prison. Sentencing guidelines in effect at the time made
him eligible for parole in 1979.
</P>
<P>
   ''The death penalty came back, but he didn't go back on death
row,'' said Elaine Tedesco, Gary Tedesco's sister.
</P>
<P>
   Trantino has lost at least nine parole bids during his 37 years
behind bars, but a three-judge appellate panel on June 9 said
parole board members ignored several key points on Trantino's
behalf, including his clean prison record since 1970.
</P>
<P>
   The panel ordered that Trantino be released to a halfway house,
but the state appealed the ruling. The state Supreme Court is
scheduled to hear arguments on Trantino's case on Sept. 25.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't think they read any of the transcripts,'' Elaine
Tedesco said of the judges' recent decision.
</P>
<P>
   DiFrancesco signed the bill next to Tedesco's mother,
76-year-old Sadie, who clutched a photograph of her 22-year-old
slain son.
</P>
<P>
   ''I can't take it no more,'' Sadie Tedesco said of the years she
has relived her son's death. ''You get numb.
</P>
<P>
   ''I haven't been myself in 37 years.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-08-22-00 1849 </TRAILER>
