<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-22 19:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> State says scores show students do well but test is questionable  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN P. McALPIN
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - Results from standardized tests show New
Jersey's fourth- and eighth-graders appear to do well in science
and math but most fourth-graders can't write well enough to pass
state standards.
</P>
<P>
   So many students did so poorly in the writing section that the
state will re-examine how those tests are scored. Forty percent of
the fourth-graders tested scored a zero, according to results
released Tuesday by the state Department of Education.
</P>
<P>
   State education officials said they don't know if it's the test
or the students.
</P>
<P>
   This is the second year for the tests designed to gauge how
students perform when compared to new, tougher classroom standards.
</P>
<P>
   Education Commissioner David Hespe warned that new tests will
show variable results from year to year, especially when new
standards are in place.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have to remember progress takes many years and it is never
linear,'' Hespe said.
</P>
<P>
   For eight-grade students, about 80 percent scored above
proficiency levels in science and language arts.
</P>
<P>
   But roughly one-third of the students failed to make the grade
on the math test.
</P>
<P>
   In fourth grade, just under 90 percent ranked proficient or
above on the science exam, roughly the same as the 1999 figure.
</P>
<P>
   Math results were better than last year. About 71 percent tested
at or above the standard. In 1999, 57 percent hit that mark.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are very pleased with the real gains in this area,'' Hespe
said.
</P>
<P>
   The state's top educator gave high marks to the students and the
test process.
</P>
<P>
   ''Overall, we think our testing program is strong. It's showing
the numbers we want with one exception,'' Hespe said.
</P>
<P>
   That glaring area is the writing exam for the fourth grade.
</P>
<P>
   ''There was a performance gap between the multiple choice
reading sets and the writing tests,'' Hespe said.
</P>
<P>
   Test supervisors reviewed the raw scores with consultants who
told the state there appears to be a problem with the way writing
samples were scored, Hespe said.
</P>
<P>
   The state will go back to the committee of teachers who drafted
the score sheet and the models, the commissioner said. The state
could recalculate the test scores for that test.
</P>
<P>
   Even if the grading standards are changed, there will not be a
great change in the overall results, Hespe said.
</P>
<P>
   That means schools must work to improve writing skills, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''This area will still be one of the most troublesome for school
districts. The problem with writing will not go away,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   School districts use these test to design programs. Teachers use
them to identify problems with particular students.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-08-22-00 1905 </TRAILER>
