<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-22 19:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lockerbie Court: Declassify Cables  </HEADLINE>
By JEROME SOCOLOVSKY
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMP ZEIST, Netherlands (AP) -- Scottish judges hearing the
Lockerbie bombing trial called on the U.S. government Tuesday to
fully declassify a batch of CIA cables containing information
provided by a Libyan informant around the time of the 1988 airliner
explosion.
</P>
<P>
   As the trial resumed following a three-week summer recess,
lawyers for two Libyan defendants accused of bombing Pan Am Flight
103 insisted the information was indispensable to their case. The
explosion over Lockerbie, Scotland, killed 270 people, including
189 Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Ranald Sutherland said Scotland's chief prosecutor should
''use his best endeavors to ensure that all the material contained
in these cables be disclosed.'' However, he added, ''we
appreciate'' that the documents are in the hands of the CIA, over
which the court has no jurisdiction.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, prosecutors insisted the information censored from the
cables was removed for reasons of U.S. national security and was
not relevant to the Lockerbie disaster.
</P>
<P>
   ''The United States considers all of this material highly
confidential,'' said Lord Advocate Colin Boyd.
</P>
<P>
   Boyd said the deleted text referred to CIA agents real and code
names, as well as locations and methods of intelligence gathering.
</P>
<P>
   Abdul Majid Giaka, who has since defected to the United States
and is in the U.S. federal witness protection program, reportedly
saw one of the defendants place a suitcase containing the bomb on
an airport conveyor belt in Malta, where all three worked for
Libyan Arab Airlines allegedly as cover for their espionage
activities.
</P>
<P>
   According to the indictment, the defendants sent the suitcase
bomb onto a flight from the Mediterranean island to Frankfurt,
Germany, where it was transferred as unaccompanied luggage onto a
feeder flight connecting with Flight 103 in London.
</P>
<P>
   Giaka is considered the closest thing the prosecutors have to an
eyewitness who can directly link the defendants to the crime.
</P>
<P>
   The 25 cables, dated Aug. 10, 1988 to Aug. 31, 1989, were sent
to Washington by CIA operatives who interviewed Giaka. The Libyan
had walked into the U.S. Embassy in Malta in August 1988 -- four
months before the Lockerbie bombing -- and offered his services to
the CIA, Boyd said.
</P>
<P>
   Giaka is expected to take the stand this week as a key witness.
He has asked to be hidden from the court by screens and electronic
voice distortion.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Taylor, a Scottish attorney for Abdel Basset Ali
al-Megrahi, showed the court copies of the documents as provided to
the defense. Large segments of text were blacked out.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors expect to wrap up their evidence in September,
handing the floor to the defense lawyers, whose case is expected to
last several months as well. The trial began May 3.
</P>
<P>
   Al-Megrahi and Lamen Khalifa Fhimah face life in a Scottish
prison if convicted on charges of murder, conspiracy to murder and
violating the British Aviation Security Act in the downing of
Flight 103 on Dec. 21, 1988.
</P>
<P>
   Also Tuesday, a man who lost his parents and sister in the plane
crash died after being struck by a train. British Transport Police
said Stephen Flannigan was walking home Sunday night in
southwestern England when he was hit. Tuesday was his 26th
birthday.
</P>
<P>
   His parents and sister died when the main part of the jet
crashed down on their home. Another brother who was not in
Lockerbie at the time of the crash has since died.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
