<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-22 20:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ga. Court Halts Man's Execution  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA (AP) -- The Georgia Supreme Court on Tuesday halted an
execution while it considers whether electrocution violates the
state's constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Alexander Williams, 32, was scheduled to die in Georgia's
electric chair Thursday night. He was 17 when he kidnapped
16-year-old Aleta Bunch from a mall, raped her, robbed her and shot
her to death in Augusta in 1986.
</P>
<P>
   Although the 5-2 order gave no reason for blocking the
execution, two justices cited the constitutional question. The
state's highest court is considering whether electrocution
constitutes cruel and unusual punishment in a separate case.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day, Williams' attorneys asked the state Board of
Pardons and Paroles to halt the execution on grounds that Williams
was only 17 when he committed the crime, is mentally ill and his
original lawyer was incompetent.
</P>
<P>
   ''The most important reason Alexander Williams should not be
executed is that the crime of which he was convicted occurred when
he was a minor,'' attorney Harold T. Daniel said after the closed
hearing.
</P>
<P>
   The board had planned another hearing for Wednesday to hear from
prosecutors, and possibly the victim's family, but postponed the
hearing after the court order.
</P>
<P>
   The Legislature this year approved and the governor signed a law
requiring lethal injection for all people sentenced to death for
crimes after May 1.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
