<HEADLINE> More West Nile Spraying as infected birds are discovered citywide  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) - New areas of the city were scheduled to be
sprayed with pesticide on Tuesday after birds and mosquitos
infected with West Nile virus were found citywide.
</P>
<P>
   City health officials say that as of Tuesday, a total of 57
infected birds and 62 infected mosquito pools have been found in
the five boroughs. Two new species of mosquitos also have been
identified as carriers of the West Nile virus.
</P>
<P>
   The pesticide Anvil is scheduled to be sprayed in two-mile areas
in northern Manhattan, including Washington Heights and Inwood and
Inwood Hill Park and Fort Tryon Park, between 10 p.m Thursday and 5
a.m. Friday.
</P>
<P>
   In the Bronx, spraying is scheduled for the north Bronx from
Marble Hill north to Riverdale along with the Kingsbridge section.
</P>
<P>
   Sections of the East Bronx, including the Country Club and
Castle Hill sections and Ferry Point Park and St. Raymond's
Cemetery, are also scheduled to be sprayed.
</P>
<P>
   Pesticide spraying is also scheduled for all of Pelham Bay Park
and Orchard Beach.
</P>
<P>
   In Brooklyn, the Bay Ridge and Bensonhurst areas of Brooklyn,
including Washington Cemetery, are scheduled to be sprayed Thursday
night.
</P>
<P>
   In Westchester, ground spraying is scheduled for Thursday night
in the communities of Rye Brook, Port Chester, Mount Vernon, Pelham
Village, Pelham Manor and Irvington.
</P>
</TEXT>
