<HEADLINE> Heat's Mourning Confident of Team  </HEADLINE>
By JAIME HERNANDEZ
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI (AP) -- Miami Heat center Alonzo Mourning has a message for
his new teammates -- get ready to work.
</P>
<P>
   ''The new guys look good on paper,'' he said Tuesday. ''You
never know until we step on the court. We need them to digest our
system.''
</P>
<P>
   Heat coach and general manager Pat Riley has given the team a
major facelift the past two months, acquiring Eddie Jones and
Anthony Mason and getting ready to trade for Brian Grant. Mourning
hopes they are willing to play for a ''hard-working, no-nonsense
guy'' like Riley and help the Heat advance deep into the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't care about the regular season,'' Mourning said.
''Winning the Atlantic Division championship, defensive player of
the year -- that's all nice. But the playoffs is what I care about.
</P>
<P>
   ''I lost some good friends in P.J. (Brown) and Mash (Jamal
Mashburn) but the game is about change, especially with Riles down
here. It's going to be different, but I hope it works out.''
</P>
<P>
   Mourning is also confident often-injured point guard Tim
Hardaway will come back with a vengeance next season, saying
Hardaway ''has a different approach'' this offseason in his
conditioning.
</P>
<P>
   But before the two begin another quest for that elusive NBA
title, they have some business to take care of at the Olympics in
Sydney next month.
</P>
<P>
   ''To know you have the opportunity to represent your country in
the first Olympics of the millennium, I am excited,'' Mourning
said. ''I want to win a gold medal with my son there watching.''
</P>
<P>
   Mourning also weighed in on the rival Knicks and the trade talk
surrounding his good friend Patrick Ewing, saying he ''has carried
the Knicks for 15 years.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Where does the loyalty lie?'' he asked. ''That defines the
business. It's not about what you've done anymore.''
</P>
</TEXT>
