<HEADLINE> Brazil's Soccer Coach Investigated  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) -- Prosecutors are examining the bank
records of Brazil national soccer team coach Wanderley Luxemburgo
as part of an investigation into charges of tax evasion.
</P>
<P>
   Investigations began in 1997 after a woman who identified
herself as a former aide to Luxemburgo testified she bought and
sold assets at auctions for Luxemburgo in her name, the Brazilian
soccer federation said Tuesday, responding to a report in the O Dia
newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   Luxemburgo has denied the allegations.
</P>
<P>
   The woman, Renata Carla Moura Alves, later filed a worker's
compensation law suit against Luxemburgo, claiming that he had
fired her after she testified against him, O Dia reported. The
court ruled in her favor after Luxemburgo failed to appear in
court, the newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
   The federation did not comment on the suit, but said the
investigation has had no affect on Luxemburgo's performance as
coach.
</P>
