<HEADLINE> 6-Year-Old Inspires Vancouver Team  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WILLIAMSPORT, Pa. (AP) -- After surviving surgery to remove a
brain tumor in mid-June, 6-year-old Tyler ''TJ'' Jacobs wasn't
about to let anything as minor as a cross-country flight keep him
from seeing his favorite team.
</P>
<P>
   That's why on Tuesday, when Vancouver, Wash., took the field
against Goffstown, N.H., in the Little League World Series, TJ, his
mother Laura and brother Austin were in the second row of Howard J.
Lamade Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's been a great inspiration for him,'' Laura Jacobs said.
''It's given him something to really remember. The team's made him
feel so special and they've really done all they could to make him
feel like part of the team.''
</P>
<P>
   The Jacobs family arrived in Williamsport early Tuesday morning
after leaving Washington on his first-ever plane ride at 6 a.m. on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   He got to visit the team, wish them good luck and give them all
high-fives before the game.
</P>
<P>
   The team repaid him, rallying from a 4-0 deficit to beat
Goffstown 6-4 on Dustin Corl's two-run homer in the bottom of the
seventh inning.
</P>
<P>
   One of the first things Corl did after the game was autograph
the ball and give it to TJ.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think TJ was a big part of this game,'' Corl said, ''We
didn't want to lose this game because TJ had traveled all the way
across the country just to see us play.
</P>
<P>
   ''He gave us the spirit to come back and work out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Due to the length of the flight and the fact that TJ won't be
fully recovered until the end of September, Laura Jacobs and his
doctors weren't sure that he could handle the trip.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting in the stands with her sons, Laura said she thought she
made the right decision.
</P>
<P>
   Jacobs, a T-ball player himself, has served as the inspiration
for the Vancouver team all summer.
</P>
<P>
   The team became involved with TJ after his mother wrote the
squad a letter asking if they could possibly dedicate a game to
him.
</P>
<P>
   Manager Tom Peavey read the note to the team and asked player
Jay Ponciano what he thought of the idea. Ponciano suggested
dedicating the rest of the season to TJ.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Jacobs credits the team with giving TJ something to think
about while he recuperates.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Ponciano said TJ has taught him there's more to life
than baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Being the inspiration for a team means media attention, however,
which is something TJ isn't familiar with.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's kind of shy and overwhelmed with everything,'' Ponciano
said. ''But I know he's happy.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: http://www.littleleague.org
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
