<HEADLINE> Lawmakers Mull Calif. Power Plans  </HEADLINE>
By JENNIFER KERR
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) -- New proposals for helping San Diego
residents strapped by soaring electric bills surfaced Tuesday, with
the governor requesting federal aid and Assembly Republicans
suggesting refunds.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Gray Davis sent President Clinton a letter asking him to
provide energy assistance for low-income residents.
</P>
<P>
   Assembly Republicans, meanwhile, proposed spending $300 million
to cover refunds for major power customers, including hospitals,
schools and businesses not covered by a state-ordered rate
rollback.
</P>
<P>
   They also asked the Democratic governor to call a special
session next month to pass legislation making it easier to build
power plants. The Legislature is scheduled to leave for the year
next week.
</P>
<P>
   Deregulation, approved by lawmakers four years ago, was supposed
to lower rates. Instead, increases in population and power use due
to the high-tech boom have caused power shortages, more than
doubling rates in San Diego County and southern Orange County.
</P>
<P>
   The Assembly is considering a measure that would force San Diego
Gas &AMP; Electric to scale back rates to those in effect June 1,
before the increases began. The bill, sponsored by two San Diego
Democrats, already has Senate approval.
</P>
<P>
   Four of San Diego County's five supervisors roamed the Capitol
on Tuesday lobbying for the bill and telling lawmakers and
reporters that small businesses will be ruined unless approval
comes quickly.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, the state Public Utilities Commission ordered the
utility to cut rates for most San Diego residents, small businesses
and school districts who don't use more than 1,500 kilowatt hours a
month. The San Diego County supervisors said that was not enough.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: Read the Davis bill, AB2290, at
http://www.sen.ca.gov
</P>
<P>
   California PUC: http://www.cpuc.ca.gov
</P>
<P>
   California Energy Commission: http://www.energy.ca.gov/siting
cases
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
