<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-22 20:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Armed Militiamen In E. Timor  </HEADLINE>
By HEATHER PATERSON
<TEXT>
<P>
   DILI, East Timor (AP) -- Growing numbers of armed
anti-independence militiamen are infiltrating the new country of
East Timor, raising fears of more attacks, a U.N. peacekeeping
officer said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Norwegian Col. Brynjar Nymo, a U.N. peacekeeping spokesman, said
frightened villagers reported seeing at least 10 militia gangs,
numbering about 120 fighters, active in East Timor after crossing
from Indonesian West Timor in recent weeks.
</P>
<P>
   East Timor, the eastern half of the island of Timor, voted to
secede from Indonesia a year ago in a U.N.-sponsored ballot. The
vote triggered a destructive rampage by anti-independence militias
backed by Indonesia. Most of the violence ended after the arrival
of international forces, led by Australia.
</P>
<P>
   The United Nations is administering East Timor during its
transition to full independence. Indonesia still holds West Timor.
</P>
<P>
   Clashes between pro-Indonesia groups and peacekeepers have
become more frequent recently and there is growing speculation that
sections of Indonesia's military have been arming and training the
gangs.
</P>
<P>
   The United Nations has complained repeatedly that militiamen are
using West Timor as a base for border incursions.
</P>
<P>
   Security in East Timor's capital, Dili, and along the border was
tightened ahead of the first anniversary of the independence ballot
Aug. 30.
</P>
<P>
   Security was also beefed up for a meeting Monday in Dili of
independence leaders who were taking their first steps toward
self-rule and the end of the U.N. administration.
</P>
<P>
   Tens of thousands of people fled last year's mayhem for refugee
camps in Indonesian West Timor. Most refugees have since returned
to East Timor, but about 80,000, mainly militiamen and their
families, remain in the camps.
</P>
<P>
   Nymo, the U.N. spokesman, said there are concerns that some
militia groups are bent on more violence, but others might be
considering a peaceful return to their villages. One gang contacted
a local Roman Catholic priest who told U.N. civilian police that
the men wanted to return to East Timor, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''This a welcome twist,'' Nymo said.
</P>
<P>
   He said many militiamen had long heard false rumors of U.N.
atrocities in East Timor and wanted to see for themselves before
deciding whether to return.
</P>
<P>
   East Timor has inherited five centuries of neglect by Portugal,
the former colonial master, and 25 years of violent Indonesian rule
that brought at least 100,000 deaths.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-22-00 2051 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000822.0174 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-22 20:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kashmir Leader To Call For Truce  </HEADLINE>
By QAISER MIRZA
<TEXT>
<P>
   SRINAGAR, India (AP) -- A separatist rebel leader in India's
Kashmir region said Tuesday that efforts were being made to revive
peace talks and that his group would call a truce in the coming
weeks, a news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
   The Hezb-ul Mujahedeen, the principal guerrilla group in Kashmir
fighting to secede from India, had declared a unilateral cease-fire
last month saying it was ready to talk peace with the Indian
government.
</P>
<P>
   But the group ended the cease-fire two weeks later when New
Delhi refused to include Pakistan in the talks.
</P>
<P>
   ''Attempts are being made to resolve the deadlock between the
government and the militants,'' said Abdul Majid Dar, the group's
top commander, told the Current News Service. ''Hopefully within
the coming two months, again there will be a cease-fire.''
</P>
<P>
   But Dar maintained that any talks would have to include
Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
   ''The only solution to the Kashmir problem is tripartite
talks,'' Dar said. ''Without the participation of Pakistan there is
no solution possible for the people of Kashmir.''
</P>
<P>
   Kashmir is divided between India and Pakistan but both countries
claim to the entire territory. India and Pakistan have fought two
of their three wars over Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
   India has refused to talk to Pakistan, whom it accuses of arming
and funding the 11-year-old insurgency in Kashmir that has killed
25,000 people. Pakistan says it supports the Kashmiris but denies
providing material aid to the guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
   On Aug. 15, India's Independence Day, Prime Minister Atal Bihari
Vajpayee reiterated his government's stand that India will not talk
to Pakistan until it stopped its support for what he called
cross-border terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   The Hezb-ul Mujahedeen, has taken responsibility for a series of
violent crimes in Kashmir, including a lethal car bombing in August
that killed 13 policemen and a photojournalist and injured 24
others.
</P>
<P>
   Dar said the Hezb-ul-Mujahideen had the interest of the people
of Kashmir at heart and that was why they were restarting the
talks.
</P>
<P>
   ''If bloodshed continues for 10 years, after that, parties will
have to come to the table to resolve the dispute. So it is better
to start today a meaningful dialogue.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
