<DOCTYPE> SUBDIVIDED </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-22 21:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 9 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Tuesday, Aug. 22, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
NTSB Rules on TWA 800 Crash
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The conclusion is ''inescapable'' that an explosion of
vapors in a fuel tank is what brought down TWA Flight 800 four years ago at a
loss of 230 lives, a top federal investigator said today. Investigators ''cannot
be certain'' what ignited the blast, but the most likely cause was an electrical
short in wiring inside the tank, said Bernard S. Loeb, aviation safety director
of the National Transportation Safety Board. The physical evidence, he said,
''leads to the inescapable conclusion'' that the plane was brought down by a
fuel-air explosion inside the center wing tank.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Federal Reserve Leaves Rates Alone
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Federal Reserve, citing strong productivity growth and
a moderating economy, decided today against boosting interest rates for a
seventh time in its campaign to fight inflation. While still warning about the
dangers that tight labor markets might spark inflation, Federal Reserve Chairman
Alan Greenspan and his colleagues included more upbeat language about the
economy in explaining their latest decision. It marked the second meeting at
which the central bank has left rates alone.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Hurricane Debby Disrupts Caribbean
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   SAN JUAN, Puerto Rico (AP) -- Quick-moving Debby became the first hurricane
to make landfall this season. With winds up to 75 mph, the hurricane apparently
caused little damage today on Antigua, Anguilla and other small Caribbean
islands. Forecasters said it was too early to gauge the threat to the U.S.
mainland but urged residents to monitor the storm.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Gore Faults Bush on Military
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   MILWAUKEE (AP) -- War veterans embraced Al Gore as one of their own today as
the Democratic presidential candidate swatted back at George W. Bush's assertion
that America's military is in decline. Emphasizing a resume that Bush, the Texas
governor, cannot match -- an Army tour in Vietnam, service on the House
Intelligence and Senate Armed Services committees -- Gore told a packed house at
the Veterans of Foreign Wars convention that his is no election year conversion.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Clinton: Welfare Rolls Declining
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Welfare rolls are half what they were four years ago, and
the percentage of Americans on welfare is at its lowest level in 35 years,
President Clinton said on the anniversary of the passage of welfare reform. ''In
four short years, we have seen a new emphasis on work and responsibility, as
welfare recipients themselves have risen to the challenge and made welfare what
it was meant to be -- a second chance, not a way of life,'' said Clinton, who
has used each anniversary as an opportunity to trumpet the falling rolls. In a
report, the Clinton administration said all states have met the law's
requirements.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Drug May Aid Alcoholics
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   CHICAGO (AP) -- A drug used to fight nausea in cancer patients can help the
most difficult-to-treat alcoholics significantly reduce their drinking, research
suggests. Success with the drug ondansetron comes amid a growing search for new
medications to help treat a disease that affects some 14 million Americans. In
the past half-century, just two drugs have been approved to treat alcoholism,
though studies on a number of others are under way.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Putin Visits Kin of Sub Victims
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   MOSCOW (AP) -- President Vladimir Putin flew to an Arctic naval base Tuesday
to console the families of 118 sailors killed in a submarine accident. Former
submariners wept in the streets as Russia mourned with striking openness over
the loss of the Kursk, which suffered a massive explosion and sank to the
Barents Sea floor Aug. 12.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Dow Ends Up 59; Nasdaq Rises 5
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Blue chip stocks closed higher today after the Federal
Reserve left interest rates unchanged, but technology stocks were mixed. The Dow
Jones industrial average ended up 59.34 at 11,139.15. On the NYSE, gainers
narrowly led losers. The Nasdaq rose 5.09 at 3,958.22.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Padres Beat Mets 16-1
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO (AP) -- With Mike Hampton sidelined because of a broken rib the New
York Mets' Pat Mahomes was ripped by San Diego in his spot start today, as
Damian Jackson hit his first career grand slam and Phil Nevin and John Mabry hit
consecutive second-deck homers in the Padres' 16-1 romp.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
AP NewsBrief by MARIA CODER
</SUBHEAD>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
