<HEADLINE> Clinton Back on Fund-Raising Tour  </HEADLINE>
By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON
<TEXT>
<P>
   BLOOMFIELD HILLS, Mich. (AP) -- The Democratic convention over,
the handoff to Al Gore complete, President Clinton went back to
what he has done most of this year and clearly enjoys -- raising big
bucks for Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   ''America has to be thinking about this election for us to
prevail; you can't sleepwalk through it,'' Clinton said at a
fund-raising dinner at the home of Internet entrepreneur Bill
O'Reilly.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's the whole shooting match, folks,'' he said. ''We have the
chance to build the future of our dreams for our children. We can't
sleepwalk through it.''
</P>
<P>
   At a pair of fund-raisers here and in nearby Bingham Farms,
Clinton racked up a reported $825,000 for Democratic congressional
candidates with the feature spot going to Rep. Debbie Stabenow,
D-Mich. who is challenging one-term Republican Sen. Spencer Abraham
in one of the nation's hottest Senate races.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, speaking under a white tent next to a turreted white
house in Bingham Farms, Clinton told Michigan Democrats who had
plunked down $1,000 a couple to attend that their money was well
spent.
</P>
<P>
   Electing Democrats, he said, ''helps people who can't go to
fund-raisers like this.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton plugged hard for Stabenow, who is trailing Abraham in
public opinion polls.
</P>
<P>
   ''I want her to win. She can win and she should win if all of
you do what you can to help her,'' the president said.
</P>
<P>
   The president also pitched for Gore and his vice presidential
running mate, Sen. Joseph Lieberman, D-Conn., for whom Michigan's
18 electoral votes are important.
</P>
<P>
   ''My party has a new leader and I thought he did a magnificent
job at the convention Thursday night,'' Clinton said of Gore.
</P>
<P>
   He took a jab at the tax-cut plan being pushed Gore's Republican
rival, Texas Gov. George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have worked too hard to get this country out of a ditch and
we have worked too hard to get rid of the deficit,'' he said. ''So
don't give all the surplus away in a tax cut.''
</P>
<P>
   On the issues that matter to the largest numbers of average
Americans, Clinton said, ''You've got to vote for Debbie -- and Al
and Joe.''
</P>
</TEXT>
