<HEADLINE> Ex-Chechen Cop Wins Parliament Seat  </HEADLINE>
By LYOMA TURPALOV
<TEXT>
<P>
   GROZNY, Russia (AP) -- A retired police general won elections for
a Russian parliament seat from breakaway Chechnya, officials
announced Tuesday, in a vote criticized by human rights groups for
taking place while the republic is still at war.
</P>
<P>
   Aslanbek Aslakhanov won 30.3 percent of the vote in Sunday's
elections, said Chechen Election Committee Chairman Abdul-Kerim
Arsakhanov. He beat 12 other candidates, including Adam Deniyev,
who finished second with 19.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Vote counting was delayed at many polling stations because of
security concerns.
</P>
<P>
   Russian officials said the vote is a sign of peace returning to
Chechnya. Elections for the lower house of parliament were held in
the rest of Russia in December, when intense fighting in Chechnya
made it impossible to hold a local ballot.
</P>
<P>
   But human rights groups criticized the elections because parts
of Chechnya are still in rebel hands, and most areas controlled by
Russian forces are not safe. The U.S. State Department also said
conditions were less than ideal, since international observers did
not take part and the conflict has not been settled.
</P>
<P>
   Turnout was 62.1 percent, Arsakhanov said, though rebel fighters
boycotted the vote and Chechen observers at polling stations in the
capital Grozny said the figure was probably lower.
</P>
<P>
   Aslakhanov, an ethnic Chechen who was a police major general
during the Soviet era, now heads Chechnya's Association of Law
Enforcement Workers.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, military operations continued. Russian officials
claimed Tuesday to have captured a senior rebel commander who led
the defense of Grozny before it fell to federal troops in February.
</P>
<P>
   In a news release, the Federal Security Service said it had
arrested Lechi Islamov, a prominent rebel leader accused of murder,
kidnapping and extortion. A criminal case has been opened against
him, the release said.
</P>
<P>
   The Russians have said in recent weeks that they would focus on
capturing rebel leaders rather than just skirmishing with rebel
troops.
</P>
<P>
   Also Tuesday, an official with the pro-Russian Chechen
government said Interior Ministry troops were ambushed by rebels
overnight, and that there were casualties on both sides. No
casualty figures were available.
</P>
<P>
   Russian troops withdrew from Chechnya in defeat at the end of a
1994-96 war, then moved back in last September in a bid to end the
republic's de facto independence and quash what the Kremlin called
a breeding ground for terrorists.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-22-00 2144 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
