<HEADLINE> Rockies' Helton Won't Get Much Rest  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER (AP) -- Colorado Rockies manager Buddy Bell will give Todd
Helton every opportunity in his quest to hit .400.
</P>
<P>
   Bell said Tuesday that Helton probably will get only one or two
days off in Colorado's final 36 games of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ''I wouldn't expect him to be happy if I decided he wasn't going
to play because he didn't hit this guy or that guy very good. He's
hit everybody,'' Bell said. ''I think he has a better chance to hit
.400 playing every day. Every time he goes up there he has a chance
to get a hit.''
</P>
<P>
   Helton, who has missed just two games this year, entered
Tuesday's game against the Atlanta Braves hitting .398. He is
seeking to become the first player to break the .400 barrier since
Ted Williams hit .406 in 1941.
</P>
<P>
   Williams had 185 hits in 456 at-bats when he accomplished the
feat. Helton began the night with 178 hits in 447 at-bats and
already had enough plate appearances (534) to qualify for the
batting title.
</P>
