<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-22 21:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lottery To Choose Reform Candidate  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   HELENA, Mont. (AP) -- While opposing Reform Party factions fight
over who is the party's true presidential nominee, Secretary of
State Mike Cooney will use a lottery to settle the issue for
Montana's general election ballot.
</P>
<P>
   A drawing will be conducted Thursday to determine whether Pat
Buchanan or John Hagelin will be listed as the Reform Party
candidate for the Nov. 7 general election.
</P>
<P>
   Cooney said that process is dictated by state law when a party's
choice of nominee is unclear.
</P>
<P>
   The confusion was caused when Reform Party groups backing
Buchanan and Hagelin each submitted certificates of nomination to
place their candidate on Montana's ballot. Both factions claim to
represent the party and consider their choice the legitimate
nominee.
</P>
<P>
   Party chairman Gerald Moan filed a lawsuit Tuesday in federal
court in Virginia to prevent Hagelin from claiming to be the
party's proper nominee.
</P>
<P>
   Cooney said his office would have to abide by any court order
regarding the party nominee, regardless of the outcome of
Thursday's lottery.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
