<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-22 22:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Davey Johnson Doesn't Miss a Beat  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Dodgers manager Davey Johnson came to the
ballpark with his left shoulder in bandages following arthroscopic
surgery Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Frank Jobe, the Dodgers' team physician, operated on Johnson
for almost two hours at Centinela Hospital Medical Center to repair
his labrum, which is the cartilage rim of the socket. Jobe removed
a large spur that was cutting into Johnson's rotator cuff and also
took off the end of his clavicle, where the spur was coming from.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm glad that's over, but it was something I needed to have
done because it was getting worse and worse,'' Johnson sad. ''The
last few weeks have been kind of painful, but thank goodness for
Dr. Jobe.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, who began feeling pain Aug. 8, thought he may have
injured himself working out in the weight room. But he couldn't be
sure.
</P>
<P>
   ''I didn't hit any water coolers or any concrete things, so I
know it wasn't that,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, 57, arrived at Dodger Stadium about 90 minutes before
game time. He already had made out Tuesday's lineup after Monday
night's 4-1 loss to Montreal and gave it to bench coach Jim Tracy,
who managed the Dodgers to a 3-1 record last month while Johnson
was hospitalized because of an irregular heart rhythm.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's a tough one,'' Jobe said. ''I had the same operation
about six weeks ago, and I couldn't have come down here and managed
the same day. He had substantial surgery, but he's doing extremely
well.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
