<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 10 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Tuesday, Aug. 22, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
NTSB: Fuel Tank Caused TWA Crash
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The conclusion is ''inescapable'' that an explosion of
vapors in a fuel tank is what brought down TWA Flight 800 four years ago at a
loss of 230 lives, a top federal investigator said today. Bernard S. Loeb,
aviation safety director of the National Transportation Safety Board said
investigators ''cannot be certain'' what ignited the blast, but the most likely
cause was an electrical short in wiring inside the tank. The physical evidence,
he said, ''leads to the inescapable conclusion'' that the plane was brought down
by a fuel-air explosion inside the center wing tank.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Federal Reserve Leaves Rates Unchanged
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Citing strong productivity growth and a moderating
economy, The Federal Reserve decided today against boosting interest rates for a
seventh time in its campaign to fight inflation. While still warning about the
dangers that tight labor markets might spark inflation, Federal Reserve Chairman
Alan Greenspan and his colleagues included more upbeat language about the
economy in explaining their latest decision. It marked the second meeting at
which the central bank has left rates alone.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Hurricane Debby Disrupts Caribbean
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   SAN JUAN, Puerto Rico (AP) -- Compact, quick-moving Debby became the first
hurricane to make landfall this season, hitting several small Caribbean islands
today on a northwesterly route that menaced Puerto Rico and the Bahamas
archipelago. Forecasters said it was too early to gauge the threat to the U.S.
mainland.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Clinton Back on Fund-Raising Tour
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   BLOOMFIELD HILLS, Mich. (AP) -- The Democratic convention over, the handoff
to Al Gore complete, President Clinton went back to what he has done most of
this year and clearly enjoys -- raising big bucks for Democrats. ''America has
to be thinking about this election for us to prevail; you can't sleepwalk
through it,'' Clinton said at a fund-raising dinner at the home of Internet
entrepreneur Bill O'Reilly. At a pair of fund-raisers here and in nearby Bingham
Farms, Clinton racked up a reported $825,000 for Democratic congressional
candidates with the feature spot going to Rep. Debbie Stabenow, D-Mich. who is
challenging one-term Republican Sen. Spencer Abraham in one of the nation's
hottest Senate races.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Britain Re-Arrests Belfast Militant
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) -- Police re-arrested notorious militant
Johnny ''Mad Dog'' Adairs Tuesday night as Britain moved to suppress rising
violence among the province's pro-British gangs. Police stopped Adair's car in
Belfast, ordered him at gunpoint onto the ground and handcuffed him. He was
transferred by helicopter to Northern Ireland's Maghaberry prison under the
orders of Britain's minister responsible for the province, Peter Mandelson. In
response, supporters of Adair's outlawed Ulster Defense Association, or UDA,
attacked an office, business and several homes linked to a rival faction, police
said.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Peru Chief Announces Arms Ring Bust
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   LIMA, Peru (AP) -- Opposition leaders voiced suspicion Tuesday about the
timing of President Alberto Fujimori's announcement that his shadowy security
adviser had broken a smuggling ring supplying arms to Colombian rebels. Fujimori
made the announcement Monday alongside his reclusive security chief Vladimiro
Montesinos, who spoke publicly at a news conference for the first time in a
decade. The Peruvian officials said that an international ring, headed by a
retired Peruvian army lieutenant, used parachutes to drop at least 10,000
Russian-made AKM rifles obtained in the Middle East into rebel-held Colombian
territory between March and July of 1999.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Putin Visits Kin of Sub Victims
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   MOSCOW (AP) -- President Vladimir Putin flew to an Arctic naval base Tuesday
to console the families of 118 sailors killed in a submarine accident. Former
submariners wept in the streets as Russia mourned with striking openness over
the loss of the Kursk, which suffered a massive explosion and sank to the
Barents Sea floor Aug. 12.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Tokyo Stocks Rise in Early Trading
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- Stock prices inched higher Wednesday morning following a rise
in U.S. blue chips overnight. The dollar fell against the yen. The Nikkei was up
26.98 points, or 0.16 percent, at 16,481.72 in early trading. In New York, the
Dow ended up 59.34 at 11,139.15. The Nasdaq rose 5.09 at 3,958.22.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Wizards Trade Austin to Grizzlies
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- In Michael Jordan's first trade as a front office
executive, the Washington Wizards on today sent disgruntled center Ike Austin to
the Vancouver Grizzlies for four players: Dennis Scott, Cherokee Parks, Obinna
Ekezie and Felipe Lopez. The deal gives the salary cap-strapped Wizards a needed
jolt of new blood, while it rids them of a seven-year veteran who wanted out
after losing his starting job to Jahidi White last season.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
AP NewsBrief by MARIA CODER
</SUBHEAD>
