<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-22 22:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indiana Gov. Extends Gas Tax Relief  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- The governor is continuing his suspension of
the sales tax on gasoline even though Indiana's gas prices are the
lowest in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Frank O'Bannon suspended the 5 percent tax on June 27 to
help drivers cope with prices that had skyrocketed to among the
highest in the country. The suspension was set to expire Saturday,
but O'Bannon said he wants residents to enjoy the extra savings
through the Labor Day weekend, when supply and demand often drives
prices up.
</P>
<P>
   If gas supplies and prices remain at their current level,
O'Bannon said he would lift the suspension Sept. 16.
</P>
<P>
   O'Bannon's Republican opponents say he is spending down the
state surplus while using the tax suspension to bolster his
November re-election bid.
</P>
<P>
   Indiana had the nation's lowest average cost for gasoline on
Tuesday, with drivers paying an average of $1.31, down from $1.69
in July, AAA reported.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
