<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Obituaries in the News  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated PressJane Kesner Ardmore:
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Jane Kesner Ardmore, ghost biographer for
such stars as Eddie Cantor and Joan Crawford, died Aug. 16. She was
88.
</P>
<P>
   Ardmore also wrote under the name Jane Morris.
</P>
<P>
   Her other major biographies were ''The Dress Doctor'' in 1959
with Hollywood costume designer Edith Head; ''The Self Enchanted:
Mae Murray, Image of an Era'' also in 1959, and Crawford''s 1962
autobiography ''Portrait of Joan,'' which earned the 1963
nonfiction prize from the National Federation of Press Women.
</P>
<P>
   Ardmore also wrote articles for magazines like the Saturday
Evening Post, Good Housekeeping, McCalls and Readers Digest on
Hollywood celebrities, including Michael Landon, Ingrid Bergman,
Jack Webb, Gracie Allen, Jack Benny, Bob Hope, Marlon Brando,
Loretta Young and Rock Hudson.
</P>
<P>
   Her novels included ''Women Inc.'' in 1946, which won the
fiction prize from the Indiana University Writers Conference. She
also wrote ''Julie,'' published in 1952, which was a Literary Guild
selection.
Herbert Brenner:
</P>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Former talent agent Herbert Brenner, who
guided the careers of directors Mervyn LeRoy and Raoul Walsh as
well as actors Robert Taylor and Shelley Winters, died Saturday of
a heart attack. He was 86.
</P>
<P>
   Brenner was vice president of the MCA Agency and later president
of General Artists Corp.
Tom Day:
</P>
<P>
   BUFFALO, N.Y. (AP) -- Tom Day, a standout lineman with the
Buffalo Bills' AFL championship teams of the 1960s, died Monday. He
was 65.
</P>
<P>
   Day was a member of the defensive unit that helped the Bills win
AFL titles in 1964 and 1965. Day also played for the St. Louis
Cardinals and San Diego Chargers before retiring in 1968.
</P>
<P>
   After retirement, Day worked to help former NFL players in times
of need through the retired players division of the NFL Players
Association,
Julian Richardson:
</P>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- Julian Richardson, the owner of a San
Francisco book store that served as a meeting place for black
artists and activists in the city, died Monday of heart failure. He
was 84.
</P>
<P>
   Richardson established the Marcus Bookstore in 1960, naming it
after black nationalist writer and activist Marcus Garvey.
</P>
<P>
   The store was a staple of black culture and was a gathering
place for Black Panthers supporters during the civil rights era.
</P>
<P>
   Through the years, writers such as Alice Walker, Ishmael Reed,
Terry MacMillan and Cornel West have come to the bookstore.
</P>
<P>
   Richardson studied lithography in college and opened his own
printing business. He used his skills to print books, pamphlets and
manuscripts on black culture that otherwise would have to have been
ordered from the East Coast.
Robert E. Swink:
</P>
<P>
   SANTA MARIA, Calif. (AP) -- Film editor Robert E. Swink,
nominated for Oscars for ''Roman Holiday,'' ''Funny Girl'' and
''The Boys From Brazil,'' died Aug. 15. He was 82.
</P>
<P>
   Swink joined the editorial department of RKO Radio in 1936 and
within five years worked his way into film editing. He worked on
training films in the Army Signal Corps during World War II.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to his Academy Award nominations, Swink earned a
career achievement award in 1993 from the American Cinema Editors.
</P>
<P>
   Other films edited by Swink, who retired in 1989, included
''Papillon'' and ''Rooster Cogburn.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
