<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Schourek Begins Rehab Assignment  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   PAWTUCKET, R.I (AP) -- Boston Red Sox left-hander Pete Schourek
began a 30-day rehab assignment at Triple A Pawtucket on Monday
night, allowing one hit over three innings in a 2-1 victory over
Ottawa.
</P>
<P>
   Schourek has been on the disabled list since July 21 with a
frayed left rotator cuff and bone chips in his left elbow. He was
2-9 with a 5.05 ERA in 19 starts this season.
</P>
<P>
   ''Rest and restrengthening, without having to throw a lot at
game speed, really helped,'' Schourek said. ''I didn't pick up a
ball for 10 or 11 days. I just concentrated on resting and getting
my shoulder and elbow strong again.''
</P>
<P>
   Schourek, 31, was on a 50-pitch limit. He wound up throwing 45
pitches, 25 for strikes, and allowed only a third-inning double by
Sean Mulligan and a walk. He struck out one.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was happy with the way I felt and with the way I threw,''
Schourek said. ''I felt a little rusty in the first inning, and a
little anxious. I haven't been on the mound in a game situation in
a while.''
</P>
<P>
   Schourek expects to return to Boston, but doesn't want to rush
his rehab.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'll probably throw another rehab game somewhere,'' he said.
''If everything goes well, I can increase my pitch count.
Certainly, 45 pitches isn't an absolute true test. When I get it up
to 90, 100 pitches with no problem, then I've got something to be
excited about.
</P>
<P>
   ''If I reach that point, I assume I'll be activated when they
expand rosters (on Sept. 1).''
</P>
</TEXT>
