<HEADLINE> Drunk Driver Sentenced for Killing  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   STOCKTON, Calif. (AP) -- A six-time convicted drunken driver has
been sentenced to at least 16 years in prison for driving drunk and
killing a 5-year-old boy.
</P>
<P>
   Manuel Paul Castillo, a 39-year-old unemployed construction
worker, was due to serve a jail sentence for drunken driving when
he got behind the wheel April 22 and struck a car driven by Masako
Saenz. Her son, Manuelito Saenz, was killed instantly.
</P>
<P>
   Castillo was driving with a suspended license and had more than
twice the legal blood-alcohol level when he took an illegal left
turn in his pickup truck and plowed into Saenz's compact car.
</P>
<P>
   Judge William Murray said during sentencing that Castillo had
failed to make good on many promises to turn his life around over
the years. Murray gave him a sentence of 16 years to life.
</P>
<P>
   ''I can't express my sorrow and I can't bring him back but I do
ask the court and the family to forgive me,'' Castillo told the
court.
</P>
</TEXT>
