<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ecuador Congress Leader Steps Down  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   QUITO, Ecuador (AP) -- The speaker of Ecuador's national
legislature resigned on Tuesday, breaking a three-week deadlock
over the leadership post.
</P>
<P>
   Susana Gonzales' announcement came less than an hour after
Ecuador's highest court ordered the legislature to take another
vote to determine who will head the 123-seat Congress. ''I am
stepping down from my position for a greater good, that of peace
and civic tranquility,'' Gonzales told reporters.
</P>
<P>
   President Gustavo Noboa had accused lawmakers of dragging the
country into a ''grave institutional crisis'' and refused to
recognize any legislative decisions until the leadership fight was
resolved.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez was elected with support from centrist and left-wing
lawmakers on Aug. 1 in a session marred by shoving and cursing on
the Congress floor.
</P>
<P>
   The conservative Social Christian party argued that one of its
members was entitled to the post under Ecuadorean law because its
candidates received the second highest number of votes in the 1998
general elections.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez's supporters justified her appointment, saying she had
been a member of the Social Christians until she quit in July.
Leaders of the party, which holds 25 seats, won a court order to
annul her election.
</P>
<P>
   The case was appealed to the Constitutional Tribunal, which
issued its ruling Tuesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
