<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-22 23:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton: Welfare Rolls Declining  </HEADLINE>
By D. IAN HOPPER
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Welfare rolls are half what they were four
years ago, and the percentage of Americans on welfare is at its
lowest level in 35 years, President Clinton said on the anniversary
of the passage of welfare reform.
</P>
<P>
   ''In four short years, we have seen a new emphasis on work and
responsibility, as welfare recipients themselves have risen to the
challenge and made welfare what it was meant to be -- a second
chance, not a way of life,'' said Clinton, who has used the each
year's anniversary as an opportunity to trumpet the falling rolls.
</P>
<P>
   In a report, the Clinton administration said all states have met
the law's requirements.
</P>
<P>
   The percentage of Americans on welfare has fallen from 5.5
percent when Clinton took office in 1993 to 2.3 percent in 1999,
and is now at its lowest level since 1965, the White House said.
Welfare rolls peaked in 1994 at 14.2 million people, mostly single
women and their children. They dropped to 6.3 million by December,
a 56 percent decrease.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly three-fourths of the overall decline occurred since the
new welfare law was enacted, with 1999 caseloads roughly half what
they were in 1996, the White House said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the national decline was slower in 1999 than it has been
in recent years, and welfare rolls edged up in a handful of states,
including Texas, where GOP presidential hopeful George W. Bush is
governor. They also rose in Tennessee, the home state of Democratic
nominee Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton met at the White House Tuesday with top corporate
executives who issued their own progress report on welfare.
</P>
<P>
   The nation's welfare system was dramatically improved by the
overhaul, but poor people entering the work force need help with
child care, transportation and training -- the very challenges this
group has always faced, the business executives said.
</P>
<P>
   Their report added that former welfare recipients have made
''good, productive employees.''
</P>
<P>
   Job retention rates for those workers meet and often exceed
those for employees who haven't been on welfare, according to the
report.
</P>
<P>
   But the executives say government programs are still needed to
help welfare recipients get jobs, citing child care and
transportation as the ''biggest obstacles to work.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Lawmakers should sustain or, ideally, increase resources for a
range of programs that help former welfare recipients stay on the
job,'' said the report from the Welfare to Work Partnership.
</P>
<P>
   The report recommends Congress increase tax credits and
child-care grants to cover more working parents and subsidize
transportation and housing costs so welfare recipients can get to
work more easily or move closer to their jobs.
</P>
<P>
   The 1996 welfare law encouraged recipients to enter the work
force by limiting the time they can collect benefits and requiring
them to work while on the rolls. It also offered incentives to
employers to hire welfare recipients.
</P>
<P>
   The corporate executives who signed the report include chiefs of
United Airlines, Sprint, Citigroup, Time Warner, Bank of America,
Burger King, Monsanto, United Parcel Service and IBM.
</P>
<P>
   The Welfare to Work Partnership, according to a survey of its
members, found the average starting wage of those hired from
welfare rolls is $7.80 per hour, significantly higher than the
minimum wage of $5.15, and said about three in four receive medical
benefits. More than 44 percent of hires, the report says, get a
401(k) matching savings plan.
</P>
<P>
   The report also recommends that Congress, when it revisits the
law next year, loosen the federal requirement that welfare
recipients find work while on welfare.
</P>
<P>
   The definition of a ''work activity'' should include
substance-abuse treatment, domestic violence counseling and other
special needs, it said. And Congress should give a break to workers
who need longer than five years to get off welfare because of low
starting pay, the report says.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-22-00 2331 </TRAILER>
